      </sect1>
      <sect1 id="ch0005s0001" role="Heading">
         <sect1info>
            <risinfo>
               <booktitle>Handbook for Culturally Competent Care</booktitle>
               <isbn>1316139783031</isbn>
               <chapternumber>5</chapternumber>
               <chapterid>ch0005</chapterid>
               <chaptertitle>5. People of American Indian/Alaskan Native Heritage</chaptertitle>
               <authorgroup>
                  <author>
                     <personname>
                        <firstname>Eric A.</firstname>
                        <surname>Fenkl</surname>
                     </personname>
                  </author>
                  <author>
                     <personname>
                        <firstname>Larry D.</firstname>
                        <surname>Purnell</surname>
                     </personname>
                  </author>
               </authorgroup>
               <publisher>
                  <publishername>Springer International Publishing</publishername>
               </publisher>
               <pubdate>2024</pubdate>
            </risinfo>
            <primaryauthor>
               <personname>
                  <firstname>Eric A.</firstname>
                  <surname>Fenkl</surname>
               </personname>
            </primaryauthor>
         </sect1info>
         <title>
            <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">5.1 </emphasis> Overview and Heritage</title>
         <para role="Para">This chapter provides a general overview of American Indians and Alaskan Natives (AI/AN) followed by a more detailed description of the Navajo Nation as one exemplar. Space does not permit an extensive discourse on each tribe. The 2020 census reports 9.7 million people identified as American Indian and Alaska Native alone or in combination with another race. This is a significant increase from the 5.2 million in 2010. Around 20% live in American Indian areas/reservations or Alaska Native villages. The census report is tabulated based on an AI/AN write-in response to the 2020 census race question indicating that there is a changing demographics among AI/AN. National findings indicate that the Alaska Native alone population grew 10.9% to 133,311 while the AN alone or in any combination population increased 45.6% to 241,797. A similar increase is seen in the American Indian alone population which grew 11.6% to 2,159,802 while the alone or in any combination population nearly doubled to 6,363,796.</para>
         <para role="Para">There are more than 574 federally recognized sovereign AI/AN tribes, of which 231 are Alaskan Natives and are divided into five groups: Aleuts, Northern Eskimos (Inupiat), Southern Eskimos (Yuit), Interior Indians (Athabascans), and Southeast Coastal Indians (Tlingit and Haida). In addition, there are approximately 400 non-federally recognized tribes, each with its unique customs and beliefs. Some Alaskan Natives do not mind being called Eskimos or Indians; however, some do not like to be called Native Americans or Eskimos and prefer Alaskan Native, Alaska Indian, or Inuits. The amount of Indian blood or blood quantum necessary to include enrolment requirements is dependent on each tribe. For example, the Cherokee Nation laws are based on legal documentation that demonstrates direct ties to the tribe with no blood quantum. However, the Navajo Nation requires at least one biological parent to be enrolled with the Navajo Nation, the applicant must meet the minimum ¼ Navajo blood quantum requirement. Many of the Sioux Nations from the great plains area require ¼ blood quantum and three generations of lineal descent.</para>
         <para role="Para">Indian Health Service (HIS): The Indian Health Service (IHS) was designed to fulfill the U. S. government’s role in providing health care to American Indians and Alaskan Natives (AI/AN); however, inadequate funding has left those who depend on the IHS with only limited health care.</para>
         <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
            <listitem>
               <para role="Para">Overall, AI/ANs are extremely diverse groups of people. Some are very traditional, some are highly acculturated, and some selectively combine tradition with the European American culture. Many share similar, but not exact, traditions, beliefs, and values.</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem>
               <para role="Para">AI/ANs are a particularly vulnerable population in terms of accessing health care.</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem>
               <para role="Para">High poverty rates, increasing suicides, individual high-risk health behaviors, social factors, low educational levels, chronic conditions and greater health disparities make it particularly important for accessing and receiving ongoing supportive and preventive care.</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem>
               <para role="Para">One-third of AI/ANs are in families with incomes below the federal poverty line. The median household income for American Indian and Alaska Natives is $49,906.</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem>
               <para role="Para">One in five adults has not graduated from high school; 65 % earn a high school diploma compared with 75.2% of the U. S. population. The college graduation rate is also much lower, with 9.3% compared to the national average of 20.3%.</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem>
               <para role="Para">Almost half of uninsured adults do not have a usual source of care, making it difficult to receive preventive services and timely care for acute health problems.</para>
            </listitem>
         </itemizedlist>
         <para role="Para">The IHS is divided into 12 regions, each with either hospital, clinics, or outreach areas. The regions are listed in Table <emphasis role="InternalRef">
               <link linkend="ch0005s0001ta01">5.1</link>
            </emphasis>. Federally recognized tribes are considered sovereign nations, giving them independent authority over their territories with the power to rule and make laws.</para>
         <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
            <listitem>
               <para role="Para">Although the IHS includes access to some specialty care and has established urban Indian health clinics, shortages in funding and a lack of facilities and health-care professionals have left many eligible AI/ANs struggling to obtain timely, high-quality health care.</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem>
               <para role="Para">The AI/AN population is a young population with a median age of 31 years compared with 37 years for the US overall.</para>
            </listitem>
         </itemizedlist>
         <table id="ch0005s0001ta01">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="CaptionNumber">Table 5.1</emphasis> Regions of the Indian Health Service</title>
