               <personname>
                  <firstname>Eric A.</firstname>
                  <surname>Fenkl</surname>
               </personname>
            </primaryauthor>
         </sect1info>
         <title>
            <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">7.2 </emphasis> Reflective Exercises</title>
         <orderedlist continuation="restarts" inheritnum="ignore">
            <listitem role="ListItem">
               <para>A patient wants to incorporate ginseng with prescriptive medication. What is your advice?</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem role="ListItem">
               <para>What evidence do you see with the “ethic of neutrality” among Appalachians or any other group or person?</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem role="ListItem">
               <para>Identify at least three health conditions common among Appalachians. What might you do to help decrease these conditions?</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem role="ListItem">
               <para>What tactics might you use to help decrease the high smoking rates among Appalachians?</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem role="ListItem">
               <para>How might you work with local community churches to teach health food practices and prevention of sexually transmitted infections?</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem role="ListItem">
               <para>How is <emphasis>fatalism</emphasis> displayed among Appalachians?</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem role="ListItem">
               <para>An overweight teenager is drinking 8–10 glasses of “sweet tea” on a daily basis. How might you encourage her to decrease the amount of “sweet tea” she drinks on a daily basis?</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem role="ListItem">
               <para>A close family friend whose spouse is dying of metastatic breast cancer tells you “I am wore out and don’t know how much more I can do.” What might you do to help your friend get some respite from this situation?</para>
            </listitem>
         </orderedlist>
      </sect1>
