         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0019s0001s0005" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">19.1.5 </emphasis> High-Risk Health Behaviors</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Encourage Pap smears as part of routine examinations and during other healthcare visits for women.</emphasis> Hmong women have a high incidence rate of cervical cancer, yet they are the least likely among all Asian ethnic groups to undergo screening. Contributing factors to low screening rates include lack of awareness, discomfort or pain during the procedure, embarrassment, and modesty. Failure to undergo regular gynecological examinations with Pap smears increases the risk of advanced cervical cancer.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Explain the adverse effects of cigarette smoking, promote cessation, and collaborate with schools to educate about the dangers of smoking at a young age.</emphasis> Many individuals are unaware that cigarette smoking can cause cancer. E-cigarette use is the most common form of tobacco use among Hmong adolescents.</para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0019s0001s0006" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">19.1.6 </emphasis> Nutrition</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">The Hmong people were primarily farmers, and many have developed small farms where they sell fruits and vegetables. Even Hmong living in apartments have small plots for growing vegetables, and their homes may have chicken pens in the backyards.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Rice is the primary staple of the Hmong diet. Vegetables, fish, chicken, and pork are served with the rice. Spicy peppers are used to make into a condiment that accompanies the meal.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">
                     <emphasis role="bold">It is advisable to avoid consuming raw pork due to the potential for serious health risks. Encourage physical activity and maintaining a balanced, healthy diet.</emphasis> Occasionally, a special dish called “ <emphasis>laub”</emphasis> is made with raw pork, vegetables, and spices. This increases the risk for trichinosis, therefore, many young Hmong people have started to prefer American diets.</para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0019s0001s0007" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">19.1.7 </emphasis> Pregnancy and Childbearing Practices</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Children are highly esteemed in Hmong families, and having large families is seen as an advantage. Hmong families tend to live in multigenerational households. Many older adults often assist in caring for their grandchildren.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">According to Hmong tradition, women are believed to be particularly susceptible to illnesses and misfortunes during the first 30 days after giving birth. Therefore, a woman must confine herself and follow strict postpartum practices, also known as <emphasis>nyo dua hli.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">
                     <emphasis role="bold">New mothers may not want to eat hospital food, so allowing families to bring traditional foods from home could be beneficial.</emphasis> Women are prohibited from drinking cold beverages and spicy foods during pregnancy. Postpartum, white rice and chicken soup cooked with medicinal herbs are the traditional diet for 30 days. After giving birth, women must only consume “hot” food and drink, which is believed to help the body to expel postpartum blood.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">New mothers are expected to rest after giving birth. A woman should refrain from engaging in strenuous activities, such as lifting heavy objects or doing heavy cleaning. The mother-in-law and husband help the new mother during this period.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Hmong women view regular menstruation as a sign of good health and may prefer not to use birth control methods that disrupt the regular menstrual cycle.</para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0019s0001s0008" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">19.1.8 </emphasis> Death Rituals</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Hmong funerals are unique and can last for several days. The older or more respected the person, the longer the funeral may be. Family members are expected to attend the funeral and stay for the duration. Specific rituals are required, including animal sacrifice, to honor the deceased. These animals are used to provide food for people attending the funeral. A proper burial enables the deceased to transition to the spirit world in a positive manner, which is believed to lead to reincarnation. Most Hmong people believe in the existence of multiple souls that reincarnate. One soul stays in the vicinity of the body, while another remains in the present world, overseeing and caring for the family. Rituals are conducted to honor deceased ancestors.</para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0019s0001s0009" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">19.1.9 </emphasis> Spirituality</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Traditionally, the Hmong practiced animism and ancestor worship. They use traditional or spiritual healers (i.e., shamans) to prevent and treat illnesses.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Most older and more recent immigrant Hmong adhere to traditional animist beliefs, where ancestors are revered and spirits are believed to be widely distributed in the world, residing in many inanimate objects or places such as trees, rivers, and houses. Many people believe that spirits have the power to cause harm, misfortune, illness, or death, as well as to provide protection or prevent negative events from happening. The Hmong believe that good spirits are ancestors who watch over and protect them. They also believe that a person’s souls must live in harmony to maintain good health. The Hmong consider each person to have three souls. If a person’s soul(s) wanders off or becomes frightened, it can lead to illness or death. This is called “soul loss.” A shaman must perform a soul-calling ritual, known as <emphasis>hu plig</emphasis>, to guide the soul back to the person.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">There is also a large Christian Hmong community throughout the US. The Christian Hmong have beliefs and practices that are appropriate to their religion. Some people may denounce animist beliefs and traditional Hmong practices, such as the belief in soul loss and the performance of soul-calling ceremonies by shamans.</para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0019s0001s0010" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">19.1.10 </emphasis> Healthcare Practices</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Hmong in the US often seek Western medical care, and they may also consult traditional healers or shamans who perform rituals. They may consult herbalists and undergo multiple treatments for the same condition.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Do not mistake the regular patterns of coining or cupping for abuse. Encourage the sterilization of needles.</emphasis> Some people practice home remedies such as coining or cupping. These traditional practices result in distinctive bruises, which are typically elongated or round, and are usually located over the affected area. For instance, a Hmong individual with a sore throat may exhibit bruises around the neck, while someone with chest symptoms may undergo cupping on the front and back of the chest. They believe that pricking the center of the bruise releases bad spirits; and unsterilized sewing needles are typically used for this purpose.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">One cause of illness is believed to be the loss of one’s soul. Some people, such as babies and children, are believed to have souls that struggle to remain their bodies. If the soul(s) leaves for too long, the baby can become ill or die. For this reason, parents may choose to tie a string around the baby’s neck or wrist soon after birth. Older children and adults may have strings tied around their wrists, waists, or ankles. These must remain on until they fall off naturally, as removing them too soon can result in soul loss, illness, or even death. Since immigrating to the US, the traditional strings have been replaced with gold necklaces and bracelets.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para ParaOneEmphasisChild">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Hmong people who practice shamanic ceremonies may wear amulets in small bags around their neck or waist. These contain objects that are believed to be protective against evil spirits. These should not be removed without the patient’s or family’s permission.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Inquire about patients’ herbal use upon admission.</emphasis> Some Hmong people use herbs recommended by a Hmong herbalist. Studies have shown that these herbs may possess pharmaceutical properties.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Provide a detailed explanation of the benefits of blood transfusions when required.</emphasis> More traditional Hmong people are opposed to blood transfusions and organ donation.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Caution patients about using unfamiliar herbs.</emphasis> The traditional herbs found in Laos and Thailand are difficult or impossible to obtain in the US. Traditional herbalists sometimes use plants found in the US simply because the plant resembles a plant they had used in Laos. The efficacy of these herbs is unknown and may be harmful.</para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0019s0001s0011" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">19.1.11 </emphasis> Healthcare Providers</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Shamanic ceremonies are used for treating severe illnesses that have not improved with other forms of treatment. Shamans do not choose to become shamans; the occupation is a calling. Shamans undergo extensive training for many years and learn through apprenticeships. Shaman ceremonies are conducted within the home with the entire family present. During these ceremonies, the shamans enter the spirit world to discover the reasons behind the loss of the soul or its journey to the spirit world. During a second ritual, the shaman may call the person’s spirit home, thereby restoring harmony. A shaman may sacrifice an animal to pay the spirit world and release the soul so it can return home. <emphasis role="bold">Amulets from the ceremony may be placed on the patient to protect them, and they should not be removed.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
      </sect1>
      <sect1 id="ch0019s0002" role="Heading">
         <sect1info>
