            <ulink url="mailto:Rosario.caruso@grupposandonato.it">Rosario.caruso@grupposandonato.it</ulink>
         </para>
         <para role="keywords">Heritage, Nutrition, Pregnancy, Health behavior, Spirituality</para>
      </sect1>
      <sect1 id="ch0022s0001" role="Heading">
         <sect1info>
            <risinfo>
               <booktitle>Handbook for Culturally Competent Care</booktitle>
               <isbn>1316139783031</isbn>
               <chapternumber>22</chapternumber>
               <chapterid>ch0022</chapterid>
               <chaptertitle>22. People of Italian Heritage</chaptertitle>
               <authorgroup>
                  <author>
                     <personname>
                        <firstname>Eric A.</firstname>
                        <surname>Fenkl</surname>
                     </personname>
                  </author>
                  <author>
                     <personname>
                        <firstname>Larry D.</firstname>
                        <surname>Purnell</surname>
                     </personname>
                  </author>
               </authorgroup>
               <publisher>
                  <publishername>Springer International Publishing</publishername>
               </publisher>
               <pubdate>2024</pubdate>
            </risinfo>
            <primaryauthor>
               <personname>
                  <firstname>Eric A.</firstname>
                  <surname>Fenkl</surname>
               </personname>
            </primaryauthor>
         </sect1info>
         <title>
            <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">22.1 </emphasis> Overview and Heritage</title>
         <para role="Para">Italy is a parliamentarian Republic located in Southern Western Europe. Positioned in the middle of the Mediterranean Sea, it consists of a peninsula delimited by the Alps and surrounded by islands like Sicilia and Sardinia. Its population consists of nearly 60 million inhabitants; 5.3% of them come from different countries with a million of Romanian people. However, this chapter mainly focuses on the beliefs and practices of the Italians from mainland Italy. The large populations of Italians in the United States are not a homogeneous group and vary according to acculturation, individuality, and the variant characteristics of culture as described in Chap. <emphasis role="ExternalRef">
               <ulink url="ch0001#ch0001">
                  <emphasis role="RefSource">1</emphasis>
               </ulink>
            </emphasis>. Italian Americans are concentrated in New York, New Jersey, Massachusetts, Pennsylvania, and California. Italian enclaves, or “Little Italy” areas, can be found in major cities throughout the United States.</para>
         <sect2 id="ch0022s0001s0001" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">22.1.1 </emphasis> Communications</title>
            <para role="Para">The official language of Italy is Italian; however, there are more than 20 dialects. Many second-generation Italian Americans do not speak Italian well or at all or speak in a jargon that sometimes is not understood by native Italians.</para>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para ParaOneEmphasisChild">
                     <emphasis role="bold">When a dialect-specific interpreter is not available, the interpreter should select words that have pure meanings from Tuscan Italian, which is the official language in the country (the language prompted in the Middle-Age by Dante Alighieri who is considered the Father of the Italian language).</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Italian discussions can become quite passionate, with voice volume raised and many people speaking at once. <emphasis role="bold">High voice volume does not mean anger, but rather passionate communication and this is true especially for inhabitants of the Southern parts of the country who immigrated in the United States.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Their willingness to share thoughts and feelings among family members is a major distinguishing characteristic. Positive and negative emotions and sentiments are permissible and encouraged with family members. Expressions of affection might erupt, and frequent kissing reaffirms the emotional bond among Italians.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">The typical kiss is a kiss on each cheek. Gestures demonstrate a range of feelings, from eloquence to intense anger, and are conveyed in an economical, subtle, flowing, and almost imperceptible manner. For example, a slowly raised chin means “I don’t know.”</para>
                  <para role="Para">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Observe patients for nonverbal cues to obtain the full meaning of verbal communication</emphasis>.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Touching and embracing family and friends are common. Touching between men and women, between men, and between women can be observed during verbal communication.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Past orientation is evidenced by the pride Italians take in their home country’s rich Roman heritage. A future-oriented temporality is evidenced by the importance given to planning and saving for the future. First-generation and newer immigrants view time as an approximation rather than categorically imperative; second- and third-generation Italians adhere to clock time at least in the work situation and for appointments.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">The order of first and last names is frequently reversed in Italy. Pietropaolo Vincenzo is often used when Vincenzo is the person’s first name and Pietropaolo is the last name. Nicknames are common and used among family and friends.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">A person is called by the first or given name in social situations and by a title such as Miss, Ms., Mr., Mrs., or Dr. and his or her last or family surname in the health-care environment. Ask recent immigrants the order of the name to ensure an accurate health-care record.</para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0022s0001s0002" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">22.1.2 </emphasis> Family Roles and Organization</title>
            <para role="Para">Traditional families recognize the father’s authority. The father’s decision may be accepted as a strong principle, even among his married children. To criticize one’s father is considered disrespect toward the entire family.</para>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Women usually dominate decision-making on child-rearing issues and family social events. Even though traditional roles remain strong in second- and third-generation families, a trend toward more egalitarian relationships is evolving.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Children are taught to have good manners and respect for older people. Boys and girls are encouraged to be independent and expected to contribute to the family’s support as soon as they are old enough to work. <emphasis role="bold">Adolescent girls are expected to remain virgins until they marry even; this habit is rapidly evolving.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">The home is the focus of family gatherings. Sons and daughters visit frequently during the week and after church on Sundays to share a large meal at the parents’ house.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">To many older people, the ideal living situation is to maintain one’s own home near one’s children. Older people receive respect, gratitude, and love in return for their many sacrifices.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Most Italian Americans have an actively functioning kinship and extended family system that is the primary focus of solidarity for the nuclear family. <emphasis role="bold">Because the extended family is close and frequent visits are important, Italians make special arrangements for visitation when patients are in acute or long-term care facilities.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Social status for most families comes from family lineage. Titles are more important than names. It is important to i <emphasis role="bold">dentify Italians with a title such as Mr., Mrs., Miss, Ms., or Dr. to increase compliance with health treatments and regimens.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Most do not reject another family member because of an infraction or alternative lifestyle such as divorce, living together before marriage, or being involved in a same-sex relationship. The individual is accepted without consequences.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">When the need arises, Italians foster social support referrals for gays or lesbians and assist patients in contacting dedicated services or religious groups such as Dignity USA.</para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0022s0001s0003" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">22.1.3 </emphasis> Workforce Issues</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Italians living in the United States are punctual, and rarely miss work commitments due to a cold, headache, or minor illnesses. If completing their work requires staying later, they do so.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Although the family is of utmost importance to Italians, work takes priority over family unless serious family situations arise. This cultural predisposition parallels the European American work ethic.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Because of language barriers, first-generation Italians and newer immigrants are more likely to accept assigned tasks without expecting any decision-making authority.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Italian discussions can become quite passionate, with voice volume raised and many people speaking at once. <emphasis role="bold">High voice volume does not necessarily mean anger but rather passionate communication.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0022s0001s0004" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">22.1.4 </emphasis> Biocultural Ecology</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Italians as a group have varied physical characteristics. Those from a predominantly northern background have lighter skin, lighter hair, and blue eyes, whereas those from the south of Rome, particularly from Sicily, have dark, often curly hair; dark eyes; and olive-colored skin.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">In dark-skinned patients, the skin turns ashen instead of blue in the presence of cyanosis and decreased hemoglobin levels. Examine the sclera, conjunctiva, buccal mucosa, tongue, lips, nailbeds, and palms of the hands and soles of the feet. To assess for jaundice, look at the conjunctiva and in the buccal mucosa for patches of bilirubin pigment.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Table <emphasis role="InternalRef">
                        <link linkend="ch0022s0001ta01">22.1</link>
                     </emphasis> lists commonly occurring health conditions for Italians in three categories: lifestyle, environment, and genetics.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Mediterranean-type G-6-phosphate dehydrogenase (G-6-PD) deficiency and β-thalassemia has a profound effect on drug metabolism. Because of conditions such as hypoxemia and acidosis, the ingestion of fava beans and the administration of sulfonamides, antimalarial agents, salicylates, and naphtha quinolones can exacerbate these conditions; take extra precaution when prescribing these drug therapies especially from Italians who originated from Sardinia.</para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
            <table id="ch0022s0001ta01">
               <title>
                  <emphasis role="CaptionNumber">Table 22.1</emphasis> Health conditions common to Italian Americans</title>
               <tgroup cols="2">
                  <colspec colname="c1" colnum="1"/>
                  <colspec colname="c2" colnum="2"/>
                  <tbody>
                     <row>
                        <entry>
                           <para role="SimplePara">Health condition</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                           <para role="SimplePara">Cause</para>
                        </entry>
                     </row>
                     <row>
                        <entry>
                           <para role="SimplePara">Familial Mediterranean fever</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                           <para role="SimplePara">Genetic</para>
                        </entry>
                     </row>
                     <row>
                        <entry>
                           <para role="SimplePara">G-6-phosphate dehydrogenase deficiency</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                           <para role="SimplePara">Genetic</para>
                        </entry>
                     </row>
                     <row>
                        <entry>
                           <para role="SimplePara">Thalassemia</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                           <para role="SimplePara">Genetic</para>
                        </entry>
                     </row>
                     <row>
                        <entry>
                           <para role="SimplePara">Coronary artery disease</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                           <para role="SimplePara">Genetic, environment, lifestyle</para>
                        </entry>
                     </row>
                     <row>
                        <entry>
                           <para role="SimplePara">Vogt-Koyanagi-Harada syndrome</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                           <para role="SimplePara">Genetic</para>
                        </entry>
                     </row>
                     <row>
                        <entry>
                           <para role="SimplePara">Nasopharyngeal cancer</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                           <para role="SimplePara">Lifestyle</para>
                        </entry>
                     </row>
                     <row>
                        <entry>
                           <para role="SimplePara">Stomach cancer</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                           <para role="SimplePara">Lifestyle</para>
                        </entry>
                     </row>
                     <row>
                        <entry>
                           <para role="SimplePara">Liver cancer</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                           <para role="SimplePara">Lifestyle</para>
                        </entry>
                     </row>
                  </tbody>
               </tgroup>
            </table>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0022s0001s0005" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">22.1.5 </emphasis> High-Risk Health Behaviors</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Many immigrants continue to smoke. Alcoholism also presents a risk in this group.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para ParaOneEmphasisChild">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Assess for illnesses related to smoking and alcohol misuse, especially among newer immigrants. Encourage patients to cease or decrease smoking. Incorporate anti-smoking campaigns in elementary school. Promote responsible drinking.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0022s0001s0006" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">22.1.6 </emphasis> Nutrition</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Food is symbolic of a connection between a child and the parents; food represents the product of the father’s labor, prepared with care by the mother. A mother may demonstrate her affection by feeding her family and anyone else she likes. To the average “mom,” love is a four-letter word: food.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">The diet, rich in vegetables, pasta, fruit, fish, and cheese, varies according to the region of Italy from which the individual originated. Northern Italian foods are rich in cream and cheese, resulting in a potentially high intake of fat. Southern Italian foods are prepared in red sauces, spices, and added salt and constitute the famous Mediterranean diet.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para ParaOneEmphasisChild">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Because of regional variations in food selections and preparation practices, specifically inquire about the diet, preferably during intake assessments.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Dietary staples are spaghetti, lasagna, ravioli, fettuccine, special spaghetti called linguine or trenette with pesto, tortellini, bucatini, and rigatoni. Vegetables, fresh fruit, and beans are common. Other popular Italian foods include lentils; sausage; eggplant parmigiana; salami; olive oil; espresso and cappuccino coffee; wine; ice cream (gelato); pastries such as cannoli and biscotti; and cheeses such as provolone, gorgonzola, ricotta, pecorino cheese, and parmesan cheese. Other common dishes include escarole, Caesar salad, calzone, and pizza. Table <emphasis role="InternalRef">
                        <link linkend="ch0022s0001ta02">22.2</link>
                     </emphasis> lists the Italian names of popular foods with their descriptions and ingredients. Wine is taken at almost every meal, and red wine, mixed with water, is given to children with meals to maintain healthy blood.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">A common practice in Italian alternative medicine for health promotion is eating a clove of garlic every night before going to bed to prevent upper respiratory infections. Garlic may also be worn around the neck when there is an epidemic of influenza or other upper respiratory ailments to prevent the wearer from getting the infection. Eating a fresh raw egg every morning keeps the person strong. Fresh dandelions are used to make a salad or are boiled to make soup to give the person strength.</para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
            <table id="ch0022s0001ta02">
               <title>
                  <emphasis role="CaptionNumber">Table 22.2</emphasis> Italian foods</title>
               <tgroup cols="3">
                  <colspec colname="c1" colnum="1"/>
                  <colspec colname="c2" colnum="2"/>
                  <colspec colname="c3" colnum="3"/>
                  <tbody>
