         <title>
            <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">23.1 </emphasis> Overview and Heritage</title>
         <para role="Para">Jamaica is the third largest island (next to Puerto Rico, Hispaniola, and Cuba) within a chain of islands that form the Greater Antilles in the northern area of the Caribbean Sea. Sitting between latitudes 17° and 19°N and longitudes 76° and 79°W, Jamaica is about 146 miles east to west; 22–51 miles north to south; and a total area of about 4400 miles <superscript>2</superscript>. Its highest peak (Blue Mountain) is 7404 ft (about 2.26 km) and harvests some of the richest coffee. In some places, white and yellow limestone (bauxite) runs about 8200 ft (about 2.5 km) deep. Bauxite, the ore from which aluminum is made, is found in enormous quantities and Jamaica was the largest exporter in the world. Other exports include sugarcane, banana, coffee, and tobacco.</para>
         <para role="Para">The capital of Jamaica is Kingston, located at the southeast end of the island. The currency is the Jamaican Dollar (JMD). Due to economic failure, the worth of the JMD is about $155 to $1 United States (US) dollar. The population in Jamaica is about 2.8 million people, divided amongst three counties and 14 parishes. Please see below approximate demographic and division of Jamaica in Table <emphasis role="InternalRef">
               <link linkend="ch0023s0001ta01">23.1</link>
            </emphasis> and <emphasis role="InternalRef">
               <link linkend="ch0023s0001ta02">23.2</link>
            </emphasis>.</para>
         <table id="ch0023s0001ta01">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="CaptionNumber">Table 23.1</emphasis> Demographic population of Jamaica</title>
            <tgroup cols="2">
               <colspec colname="c1" colnum="1"/>
               <colspec colname="c2" colnum="2"/>
               <tbody>
                  <row>
                     <entry>
