      <sect1 id="ch0025s0002" role="Heading">
         <sect1info>
            <risinfo>
               <booktitle>Handbook for Culturally Competent Care</booktitle>
               <isbn>1316139783031</isbn>
               <chapternumber>25</chapternumber>
               <chapterid>ch0025</chapterid>
               <chaptertitle>25. People of Jewish Heritage</chaptertitle>
               <authorgroup>
                  <author>
                     <personname>
                        <firstname>Eric A.</firstname>
                        <surname>Fenkl</surname>
                     </personname>
                  </author>
                  <author>
                     <personname>
                        <firstname>Larry D.</firstname>
                        <surname>Purnell</surname>
                     </personname>
                  </author>
               </authorgroup>
               <publisher>
                  <publishername>Springer International Publishing</publishername>
               </publisher>
               <pubdate>2024</pubdate>
            </risinfo>
            <primaryauthor>
               <personname>
                  <firstname>Eric A.</firstname>
                  <surname>Fenkl</surname>
               </personname>
            </primaryauthor>
         </sect1info>
         <title>
            <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">25.1 </emphasis> Overview and Heritage</title>
         <para role="Para">
            <emphasis>Jewish</emphasis> people, or Jews, are a group who share a common cultural, ethnic, and religious background. Individual Jewish communities are diasporic, or globally dispersed, and vary widely in their distinct practices and customs. This chapter focuses on the needs of religiously observant individuals and their families, or Orthodox Jews, but also provides an overview of widely shared forms of Jewish heritage.</para>
         <para role="Para">The central sacred scripture in Judaism is the Torah or the Five Books of Moses (Genesis, Exodus, Leviticus, Numbers, and Deuteronomy). In the Torah, Jews are referred to variously as <emphasis>Hebrews</emphasis>, <emphasis>Israelites</emphasis>, or the <emphasis>children of Israel</emphasis>. Jews regard Abraham and Sarah as their first ancestors. Abraham’s grandson, Jacob, was renamed by God as Israel (in Hebrew, “struggles with God”), and his 12 sons and their descendants became known as the children of Israel. The later terms <emphasis>Jew</emphasis> and Jewish were derived from the name Judah, one of Jacob’s sons.</para>
         <para role="Para">Distinct Jewish communities practice the religion along a wide continuum in the observance of Jewish law, or <emphasis role="bold">halakhah</emphasis>. There are three main branches of Judaism in the United States: liberal Reform, Conservative (a mix of tradition and reform), and Orthodoxy (observance of all Jewish law). Some individuals in Orthodox or ultra-Orthodox communities may choose to consult their rabbi before making important decisions regarding their lives and health, such as fertility treatment, abortion, and organ transplants. Religious observance and beliefs can be determining factors for Jews of various subgroups. For example, according to Jewish law, a child born to a Jewish mother is identified as being Jewish. However, a child born from the union of a Jewish father and a non-Jewish mother would be recognized as a Jew only by the Reform movement but not by the Conservative or Orthodox movements. Reform Judaism approves of intermarriage between Jews and Judaism, whereas the Conservative and Orthodox movements tend to oppose it.</para>
         <para role="Para">The population of Jews in the United States as of 2020 was estimated at 7.5 million people. The size of the American Jewish population grew rapidly between the mid-nineteenth and early twentieth centuries as a result of mass migration from Central and Eastern Europe. The greatest influx occurred between 1880 and 1920. Many Jews came from Russia and Eastern Europe, primarily to escape poverty, and because of legal inequality and <emphasis>pogroms</emphasis> (anti-Jewish riots or mob violence). Most families in America today are descendants of those Eastern European and Russian immigrants and are referred to as <emphasis role="bold">Ashkenazi</emphasis> Jews. <emphasis role="bold">Sephardic</emphasis> Jews, however, trace their origins to Spain, Portugal, the Mediterranean, and North Africa. <emphasis>Israelis</emphasis> are citizens of the state of Israel, which has a Jewish majority and Muslim and Christian Arab minority. Jews who trace their family roots to Middle Eastern countries, including Iraq, Yemen, and Iran are sometimes called <emphasis role="bold">Mizrahi</emphasis>, or “Eastern” Jews. <emphasis>Falasha</emphasis> are black Jews who originated in Ethiopia, most of whom emigrated to Israel starting in the mid-1980s.</para>
         <para role="Para">Throughout their history, Jews have placed a major emphasis on education and social justice through social action. American Jews support a wide range of political causes from liberal to conservative. They often have strong ties to the state of Israel and worry about the rise of anti-Jewish hostility (antisemitism). In general, this population is well educated, and a high percentage obtain higher education and pursue professional vocations.</para>
         <sect2 id="ch0025s0002s0001" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">25.1.1 </emphasis> Communications</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">English is the primary language of Jewish Americans. Although Hebrew is used for prayers and Torah study, it is generally not used for conversation. Many elderly Ashkenazi Jews who immigrated early in the twentieth century or who are first-generation Americans might speak <emphasis role="bold">Yiddish</emphasis>, a hybrid language with Hebrew and Germanic elements written in Hebrew characters. In many ultra-Orthodox communities, Yiddish is a living spoken and written language.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Many Yiddish terms have worked their way into English, such as <emphasis>kvetch</emphasis> (someone who complains a lot); <emphasis>chutzpah</emphasis> (audacity or nerve); <emphasis>bagel</emphasis> (round rolls with a hole in the middle); <emphasis>tush</emphasis>, <emphasis>tushie</emphasis>, or <emphasis>tuchus</emphasis> (buttocks); <emphasis>ghetto</emphasis> (a densely settled and often poor urban neighborhood); <emphasis>klutz</emphasis> (a clumsy person); <emphasis>shlep</emphasis> (drag or carry); <emphasis>kosher</emphasis> (legal or okay); and <emphasis>oy vey</emphasis> (oh my). For Orthodox Jews, other important terms in Yiddish include <emphasis>davenn</emphasis> (pray); <emphasis>Shabbos</emphasis> (Sabbath); <emphasis>kashrus</emphasis> (kosher food); and <emphasis>rebbe</emphasis> (rabbi).</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Common expressions include <emphasis>l’chaim</emphasis> (to life), which is said on joyful occasions and/or as a toast; <emphasis>shalom aleichem</emphasis> (peace be with you), a traditional salutation; <emphasis>mazel tov</emphasis> (congratulations); and <emphasis>shabbat shalom</emphasis> (a good and peaceful Sabbath), which is said from Friday evening at sunset until Saturday at sunset. Yiddish pronunciation differs slightly from Hebrew: for example, not Shabbat but Shabbos.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Hebrew is read from right to left, and books are opened accordingly, with the spine on the right.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Jews frequently use humor to communicate and as a coping mechanism. However, jokes that use mainstream stereotypes about Jews, such as implying that Jews are cheap, powerful, or pampered (e.g., Jewish American princess), are culturally offensive. <emphasis role="bold">Any jokes that refer to the Holocaust or concentration camps are also inappropriate.</emphasis> However, self-criticism through humor is acceptable.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Modesty, which involves humility, is a primary value, especially among Orthodox communities. It is seen in the Orthodox style of dress and culture.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Some Orthodox Jews observe the custom known as “guarding touch” ( <emphasis>shomer negiyeh</emphasis>), by restricting touch of persons of the opposite sex to their children, spouses, and other close family members. Some Orthodox men and women may refuse to shake hands or have other physical contact with adults of the opposite sex, <emphasis role="bold">and their failure to do so when one’s hand is extended should not be interpreted as a sign of rudeness.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Some Orthodox men and women may have limited social contact with persons of the opposite sex, including conversation and eye contact. <emphasis role="bold">In such cases, Orthodox men and women should only be touched when providing direct care. “Therapeutic touch” is not appropriate.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">While most Jews live for today and plan for and worry about tomorrow, history is very important in Judaism, especially of the Holocaust. They are warned to “never forget,” lest history be repeated. Therefore, their time orientation is simultaneously to the past, the present, and the future.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">The Jewish format for names follows the Western tradition. The given name comes first and is followed by the family surname. Only the given name is used with friends and in informal situations. <emphasis role="bold">In more formal situations, the surname is preceded by the appropriate title of Mr., Miss, Ms., Mrs., Rabbi, or Dr. In Orthodox circles, children are not referred to by their names until after the</emphasis>
                     <emphasis>
                        <emphasis role="bold">bris</emphasis>
                     </emphasis>
                     <emphasis role="bold">or</emphasis>
                     <emphasis>
                        <emphasis role="bold">brit milah</emphasis>
                     </emphasis>
                     <emphasis role="bold">(circumcision) (bris and brit milah are also glossary terms).</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0025s0002s0002" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">25.1.2 </emphasis> Family Roles and Organization</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">The family is the core of society, and the needs of all family members are respected.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Conservative and Reform Jews typically send school-age children to Hebrew school at least two afternoons a week after public school throughout the school year. Most Orthodox families send their children to private Jewish schools.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Children play an active role in holiday celebrations and services. Respecting and honoring one’s parents is one of the Ten Commandments. Children are expected to show gratitude to their parents for giving them the gift of life.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">In Judaism, the age of majority is 13 years for a boy and 12 for a girl, at which age children are deemed capable of differentiating right from wrong and of committing themselves to performing the commandments. Recognition of adulthood occurs during a religious ceremony called a <emphasis>bar</emphasis> or <emphasis>bat mitzvah</emphasis> (son or daughter of the commandment). This rite of passage is usually accompanied by a celebration.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">The goal of the Orthodox family is to observe and raise children to observe <emphasis>halakhah</emphasis> (Code of Jewish Law), which emphasizes maintaining health, promoting education, and helping others.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Women who follow the Jewish laws of family purity must physically separate themselves from all men during their menstrual periods and for 7 days after, at which time they visit <emphasis>mikveh</emphasis>, a ritual bath. No man may touch a woman or sit where she sat until she has been to the <emphasis>mikveh</emphasis>.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Older people receive respect, especially for the wisdom they must share. Honoring one’s parents is a lifelong endeavor; one is obligated to maintain their dignity by feeding, clothing, and sheltering them, even if they experience senility.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">The Bible, as interpreted by Orthodox Jews, prohibits intercourse between men but says nothing about sex between women. Some of the objections to gay and lesbian lifestyles include the inability of these unions to fulfill the commandment of procreation and the possibility that acting on the recognition of one’s homosexuality could ruin a marriage. The liberal movements within Judaism support legal and social equality for lesbians and gays, and welcome them as members of the community. <emphasis role="bold">Do not disclose same-sex relationships to others.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0025s0002s0003" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">25.1.3 </emphasis> Workforce Issues</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Jews who observe the Sabbath will not work from Friday evening to Saturday evening. The definition of “work” in Jewish law includes driving and using phones and many other forms of technology.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para ParaOneEmphasisChild">
                     <emphasis role="bold">They may work on the Sabbath in critical jobs such as health care when needed. They may work on Sundays.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Jewish staff should be allowed to request off the major Jewish holidays. <emphasis role="bold">Be sensitive to the needs of Jewish staff and recognize the holiness of the Sabbath, taking into account current US Equal Employment Opportunity Commission laws.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Judaism’s beliefs are consistent with the values that American society places on the individual and family. For some newer Jewish immigrants, especially the elderly, English may pose a challenge. <emphasis role="bold">Speak clearly and ask for clarification of understanding from those for whom English is a second language.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Most Jews believe in autonomy and willingly take leadership positions in the workforce when the need arises.</para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0025s0002s0004" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">25.1.4 </emphasis> Biocultural Ecology</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Skin coloring for Ashkenazi Jews ranges from fair skin and blonde or red hair to darker skin and brunette hair. Sephardic Jews have slightly darker skin tones and hair coloring, similar to people from the Mediterranean area. There also are Jewish groups throughout Africa who are black, most notably the <emphasis>Falasha</emphasis> from Ethiopia.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Genetic risk factors vary based on whether the family emigrated from Ashkenazi or Sephardic areas. There is a greater incidence of some genetic disorders among Ashkenazi individuals. Most of these disorders are autosomal recessive, meaning that both parents carry the affected gene.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Table <emphasis role="InternalRef">
                        <link linkend="ch0025s0002ta01">25.1</link>
                     </emphasis> lists commonly occurring health conditions for Jews in three categories: lifestyle, environment, and genetics.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Ashkenazi Jews have a higher rate of side effects with clozapine; 20% develop agranulocytosis.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para ParaOneEmphasisChild">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Test for agranulocytosis when Jewish patients are prescribed clozapine.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
            <table id="ch0025s0002ta01">
               <title>
                  <emphasis role="CaptionNumber">Table 25.1</emphasis> Health conditions common to Jews</title>
               <tgroup cols="2">
                  <colspec colname="c1" colnum="1"/>
                  <colspec colname="c2" colnum="2"/>
                  <tbody>
                     <row>
                        <entry>
                           <para role="SimplePara">Health conditions</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                           <para role="SimplePara">Causes</para>
                        </entry>
                     </row>
                     <row>
                        <entry>
                           <para role="SimplePara">Tay-Sachs disease</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                           <para role="SimplePara">Genetic</para>
                        </entry>
                     </row>
                     <row>
                        <entry>
                           <para role="SimplePara">Gaucher’s disease</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                           <para role="SimplePara">Genetic</para>
                        </entry>
                     </row>
                     <row>
                        <entry>
                           <para role="SimplePara">Canavan’s disease</para>
                        </entry>
