         </sect1info>
         <title>
            <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">29.2 </emphasis> Reflective Exercises</title>
         <orderedlist continuation="restarts" inheritnum="ignore">
            <listitem role="ListItem">
               <para>Identify three common health conditions among Puerto Ricans. What educational recommendation would you make to decrease them?</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem role="ListItem">
               <para>Explain the “hot” and “cold” theory of foods and illnesses. If you are unfamiliar with the foods, what might you do to learn more about them?</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem role="ListItem">
               <para>Describe Puerto Rican communication practices, including temporality and punctuality.</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem role="ListItem">
               <para>What are men’s and women’s roles in the traditional Puerto Rican culture?</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem role="ListItem">
               <para>What are acceptable fertility control practices for traditional Puerto Ricans? How might they view the use of condoms?</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem role="ListItem">
               <para>Explain Santería. For what conditions would a Puerto Rican cult a practitioner of Santería?</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem role="ListItem">
               <para>What are some traditional practices for pregnancy?</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem role="ListItem">
               <para>Does the sex of the provider raise any concerns? If yes, please explain the stated reasons.</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem role="ListItem">
               <para>What might you do to get allopathic and traditional practitioners to work together?</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem role="ListItem">
               <para>Identify the death and funeral practices of traditional Puerto Ricans.</para>
            </listitem>
         </orderedlist>
      </sect1>
