            <emphasis role="BookTitle">Handbook for Culturally Competent Care</emphasis>
         </para>
         <para role="ChapterDOI">
            <ulink url="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-031-70492-5_30">https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-031-70492-5_30</ulink>
         </para>
         <para role="AuthorGroup">
            <emphasis role="Author">
               <emphasis role="AuthorName">Tatayana Maltseva</emphasis>
               <superscript>
                  <link linkend="ch0030">1</link>
               </superscript> and </emphasis>
            <emphasis role="Author">
               <emphasis role="AuthorName">Irina Rozenfeld</emphasis>
               <superscript>
                  <link linkend="ch0030">2</link>
               </superscript>
            </emphasis>
         </para>
         <para role="AffiliationText">Nicole Wertheim College of Nursing and Health Sciences, Florida International University, Miami, FL, USA</para>
         <para role="AffiliationText">Dr. Kiran C. Patel College of Osteopathic Medicine, Nova University, Fort Lauderdale, FL, USA</para>
         <para role="Contact">
            <emphasis role="AuthorName">Tatayana Maltseva</emphasis> (Corresponding author)<?lb?>
            <emphasis role="ContactType">Email: </emphasis>
            <ulink url="mailto:bogopolt@fiu.edu">bogopolt@fiu.edu</ulink>
         </para>
         <para role="Contact">
            <emphasis role="AuthorName">Irina Rozenfeld</emphasis><?lb?>
            <emphasis role="ContactType">Email: </emphasis>
            <ulink url="mailto:rozenfel@nova.edu">rozenfel@nova.edu</ulink>
         </para>
         <para role="keywords">Russian and ethnic languages, Gender roles, Family roles, Childbearing practices, Alternative lifestyles, Diseases and health conditions, Variations in drug metabolism, High-risk health behaviors, Death rituals, Spirituality</para>
      </sect1>
      <sect1 id="ch0030s0001" role="Heading">
         <sect1info>
            <risinfo>
               <booktitle>Handbook for Culturally Competent Care</booktitle>
               <isbn>1316139783031</isbn>
               <chapternumber>30</chapternumber>
               <chapterid>ch0030</chapterid>
               <chaptertitle>30. People of Russian Heritage</chaptertitle>
               <authorgroup>
                  <author>
                     <personname>
                        <firstname>Eric A.</firstname>
                        <surname>Fenkl</surname>
                     </personname>
                  </author>
                  <author>
                     <personname>
                        <firstname>Larry D.</firstname>
                        <surname>Purnell</surname>
                     </personname>
                  </author>
               </authorgroup>
               <publisher>
                  <publishername>Springer International Publishing</publishername>
               </publisher>
               <pubdate>2024</pubdate>
            </risinfo>
            <primaryauthor>
               <personname>
                  <firstname>Eric A.</firstname>
                  <surname>Fenkl</surname>
               </personname>
            </primaryauthor>
         </sect1info>
         <title>
            <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">30.1 </emphasis> Overview and Heritage</title>
         <para role="Para">The Russian Federation (Russia), the largest country in the world with a population of 141.5 million, is composed of 21 republics, several regions, and multiple provinces. Russian geography consists of two continents: Asia and Europe. The multicultural diaspora of Russians shows the diversity of acculturation, individuality, and the variant characteristics of culture (see Chap. <emphasis role="ExternalRef">
               <ulink url="ch0001#ch0001">
                  <emphasis role="RefSource">1</emphasis>
               </ulink>
            </emphasis>) as well as the physical size of the country. There are approximately around 2.9 million Russian Americans living in the United States. This chapter focuses on Russians who are immigrants to the United States. Many Russians are very well educated. Given the complexity of Russian immigration, most of the information in this chapter pertains to people of Russian heritage who emigrated in the latter part of the twentieth century and at the beginning of the twenty-first century.</para>
         <para role="Para">Everyone could obtain higher education in the former Soviet Union. However, upon arrival to the United States, many highly qualified and educated Russian immigrants have difficulty in practicing their profession and securing employment in their specialties. This contributes to diminishing their self-esteem.</para>
         <sect2 id="ch0030s0001s0001" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">30.1.1 </emphasis> Communications</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">The official language of Russia is Russian. However, most educated Russians in the United States speak English to some extent because scientific literature in Russia is published in English.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Many Russians do not understand medical language and have difficulty communicating abstract concepts or understanding American dialects. <emphasis role="bold">It is recommended to use a professional interpreter and speak slowly and clearly with a medium tone of voice and refrain from a loud conversation when communicating with Russian immigrants.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Older Jewish immigrants speak <emphasis role="bold">Yiddish</emphasis>. Younger Jewish immigrants usually do not speak Yiddish because of lack of resources in learning Yiddish in Russia.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Punctuality is a cultural standard, and many Russians arrive early for their scheduled appointments. It is customary for Russian immigrants to take medications until symptoms disappear and save the remaining for future use. Russians prepare food and essential supplies for current and future usage. It is common for them to have an abundant stock of items for many days and weeks ahead. It is also customary for Russian immigrants to borrow medications from their Russian friends and neighbors. <emphasis role="bold">Explain the necessity of taking all medications on a regular basis as prescribed, emphasize that some prescriptions can be refilled, and use only medications prescribed to them.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Direct eye-to-eye contact is maintained among family and friends. Speech is usually clear and concise in most situations. Most Russians prefer a clear action plan instead of an uncertain dialog without a plan or goals.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para ParaOneEmphasisChild">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Eye contact is not usually maintained when speaking with government officials or authority figures. Direct eye contact during meetings and communicating with authority figures may be perceived as an invasion of privacy and may feel uncomfortable during the conversation.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Russians accept touch in healthcare settings but prefer not to be hugged or kissed by strangers. A handshake is acceptable.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Russians do not appreciate nonverbal gestures such as standing with hands inserted into pockets or arms crossed over the chest; neither do they appreciate slouching postures when being interviewed. Many Russians prefer to seek care from Russian-speaking healthcare providers. They are prone to seek multiple consultations from different providers until they develop trust with a provider.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para ParaOneEmphasisChild">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Address Russians by their last name and title such as Mr., Mrs., Miss, Ms., or Dr. You can greet patients with a handshake.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0030s0001s0002" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">30.1.2 </emphasis> Family Roles and Organization</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Family, children, and older adults are highly respected and valued. It is customary for Russians to have extended family living together for communication and support.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Decision-making among current immigrants is usually democratic. They prefer to consult with their parents and oldest children in the decision-making process. <emphasis role="bold">Ask patients who they want to be a healthcare surrogate and include them in medical decisions.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">It is common in Russian culture for grandparents to take care of their grandchildren while their parents are at work. <emphasis role="bold">Include grandparents and older family members in health education for their grandchildren.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Older parents live with their children when self-care is a concern. It is customary for Russians not to place their elderly parents in long-term care facilities. Russians ask for help from friends and other family members to take care of their aging parents.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para ParaOneEmphasisChild">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Help families to prevent caregiver burden. Provide resources about long-term care facilities if needed and encourage the family to visit the facility before a decision is made to place a family member there.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Children of all ages are expected to succeed in school, obtain a higher education, help care for older family members, and do household chores in a timely matter.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Adolescents are not expected to engage in sexual activity. Sexual and contraceptive education is still lacking in Russia. Acculturation to the American culture and lack of traditional family roles may predispose young Russian immigrants to high-risk behaviors, unprotected sexual activities, substance usage, and unexpected pregnancy.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Divorce is accepted without stigma. Same-sex marriages are not supported by Russians even though the Russian penal code was revised in 1997 and homosexuality is no longer considered a crime. However, even now, many hide their homosexuality from the family in fear of rejection.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para ParaOneEmphasisChild">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Do not disclose sexual orientation, particularly same-sex orientation, to family members.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0030s0001s0003" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">30.1.3 </emphasis> Workforce Issues</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Russians practice positive politeness, respect, and accountability in the workplace. They value time and support the rule of work and society. Not showing up for an appointment or to work without prior notification is considered disrespectful in Russian culture.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">When negotiating work contracts or project implementation, Russians express their passion for completing the project and invest considerable time and effort in supporting decisions.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">With colleagues and friends, Russians communicate directly, which is considered a sign of respect and sincerity.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Russians may practice non-direct eye contact when speaking with government officials, a practice common in Russia where making eye contact with government officials could lead to questioning, invasion of personal space, or disrespect. <emphasis role="bold">Do not assume that the lack of eye contact means the person is not paying attention, does not care, or not providing correct information.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">The tone of voice may be loud, as Russians prefer to prove their point of view by articulating loudly. <emphasis role="bold">Do not interpret a loud voice volume as a sign of anger.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0030s0001s0004" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">30.1.4 </emphasis> Biocultural Ecology</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Russians who have immigrated to the United States and elsewhere are predominately white Caucasians and have a physical structure like other white Americans, making them prone to skin cancer.</para>
                  <para role="Para ParaOneEmphasisChild">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Encourage the use of sunblock and instruct all family members about the dangers of skin cancer.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Table <emphasis role="InternalRef">
                        <link linkend="ch0030s0001ta01">30.1</link>
                     </emphasis> lists commonly occurring health conditions for Russians in three categories: lifestyle, environment, and genetics.</para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
            <table id="ch0030s0001ta01">
               <title>
                  <emphasis role="CaptionNumber">Table 30.1</emphasis> Health conditions common to Russians</title>
               <tgroup cols="2">
                  <colspec colname="c1" colnum="1"/>
                  <colspec colname="c2" colnum="2"/>
                  <tbody>
                     <row>
                        <entry>
                           <para role="SimplePara">Health conditions</para>
                        </entry>
