         </sect1info>
         <title>33. People of Turkish Heritage</title>
         <para role="ChapterCopyright">© The Author(s), under exclusive license to Springer Nature Switzerland AG 2024</para>
         <para role="ContextInformationAuthorEditorNames">E. A. Fenkl, L. D. Purnell<emphasis role="CollaboratorDesignation"> (eds.)</emphasis>
         </para>
         <para role="ContextInformationBookTitles">
            <emphasis role="BookTitle">Handbook for Culturally Competent Care</emphasis>
         </para>
         <para role="ChapterDOI">
            <ulink url="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-031-70492-5_33">https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-031-70492-5_33</ulink>
         </para>
         <para role="AuthorGroup">
            <emphasis role="Author">
               <emphasis role="AuthorName">Marshelle Thobaben</emphasis>
               <superscript>
                  <link linkend="ch0033">1</link>
               </superscript> and </emphasis>
            <emphasis role="Author">
               <emphasis role="AuthorName">Sema Kuguoglu</emphasis>
               <superscript>
                  <link linkend="ch0033">2</link>
               </superscript>
            </emphasis>
         </para>
         <para role="AffiliationText">Nursing, Cal Poly Humboldt, Arcata, CA, USA</para>
         <para role="AffiliationText">Nursing, Medipol University, Istanbul, Turkey</para>
         <para role="Contact">
            <emphasis role="AuthorName">Marshelle Thobaben</emphasis><?lb?>
            <emphasis role="ContactType">Email: </emphasis>
            <ulink url="mailto:Marshelle.Thobaben@humboldt.edu">Marshelle.Thobaben@humboldt.edu</ulink>
         </para>
         <para role="keywords">Uralic-Altaic language with 20 dialects, Cultural communication patterns, Format for names, Biological variations, Diseases and health conditions, High-risk behaviors, Maternity practices, Death rituals, Spirituality, Alternative life styles, Traditional practices</para>
      </sect1>
      <sect1 id="ch0033s0001" role="Heading">
         <sect1info>
            <risinfo>
               <booktitle>Handbook for Culturally Competent Care</booktitle>
               <isbn>1316139783031</isbn>
               <chapternumber>33</chapternumber>
               <chapterid>ch0033</chapterid>
               <chaptertitle>33. People of Turkish Heritage</chaptertitle>
               <authorgroup>
                  <author>
                     <personname>
                        <firstname>Eric A.</firstname>
                        <surname>Fenkl</surname>
                     </personname>
                  </author>
                  <author>
                     <personname>
                        <firstname>Larry D.</firstname>
                        <surname>Purnell</surname>
                     </personname>
                  </author>
               </authorgroup>
               <publisher>
                  <publishername>Springer International Publishing</publishername>
               </publisher>
               <pubdate>2024</pubdate>
            </risinfo>
            <primaryauthor>
               <personname>
                  <firstname>Eric A.</firstname>
                  <surname>Fenkl</surname>
               </personname>
            </primaryauthor>
         </sect1info>
         <title>
            <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">33.1 </emphasis> Overview and Heritage</title>
         <para role="Para">The Turkish diaspora in the United States is primarily concentrated in states such as New York, California, New Jersey, and Florida. The community comprises individuals from diverse backgrounds, with many coming from elite and upper-middle-class segments. Education holds considerable value in Turkish culture, and a substantial number of Turkish Americans hold advanced degrees, reflecting their commitment to academic pursuits. The Turkish community in the United States exhibits a wide array of beliefs and practices influenced by factors such as acculturation, individuality, and varying cultural characteristics (discussed in Chap. <emphasis role="ExternalRef">
               <ulink url="ch0001#ch0001">
                  <emphasis role="RefSource">1</emphasis>
               </ulink>
            </emphasis>).</para>
         <para role="Para">Prior to its independence, Türkiye had already initiated a process of Westernization. However, it was under the leadership of its former president, Mustafa Kemal Atatürk, that Westernization and secularism became synonymous with the country’s transformation. From 1923 to 1938, Atatürk implemented numerous progressive reforms, which included the ban on the traditional fez, the prohibition of polygamy, the establishment of civil marriage contracts, the abolition of communal law for ethnic minorities, the transition from Islamic law to a civil law legal system, the promotion of nationalism and pride, educational and cultural reforms, the compulsory adoption of surnames, the shift of the weekly day of rest from Friday to Sunday, and the election of 17 female deputies to the National Assembly.</para>
         <para role="Para">Even after his passing on November 10, 1938, Mustafa Kemal Atatürk remains highly revered as the founding father of Türkiye, given his transformative impact on the nation’s social, political, and cultural landscape.</para>
         <sect2 id="ch0033s0001s0001" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">33.1.1 </emphasis> Communications</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Turkish, spoken by approximately 90% of the population, employs a linguistic structure that does not differentiate between gender-specific pronouns, such as “he” and “she,” or possessive forms like “her” and “his.” However, it is noteworthy that Turkish does maintain a distinction between formal and informal forms of the second-person singular pronoun “you.” This linguistic characteristic reflects the societal emphasis on hierarchical status within Turkish culture.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">The pronunciation of Turkish names can pose challenges for Americans, and others, due to historical and script-based differences. Up until 1928, the Turkish language was transcribed using the Arabic script. However, guided by Atatürk’s initiatives, a distinct Turkish alphabet based on the Latin script was introduced. This modern Turkish alphabet bears similarities to the English counterpart but lacks the letters “w” and “x.” Furthermore, the Turkish alphabet accommodates certain distinctive phonetic nuances. For instance, certain sounds are represented by an undotted “i,” as well as accented “ö” and “ü,” while a “ç” with a cedilla signifies sounds akin to “sh” and “ch.” These nuanced aspects of the Turkish alphabet mirror the phonetic intricacies of the language and contribute to the distinctive pronunciation of Turkish names.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Elevated vocal tones are common in Turkish communication, indicating enthusiasm rather than anger. Simultaneous speech or interruptions during discussions are not inherently rude, except when a person of lower status interrupts a higher-status individual. <emphasis role="bold">Do not interpret speaking in a loud voice as anger.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">In Turkish society, there is a prevailing emphasis on group affiliation over individualism. Identity is often shaped by factors such as familial ties, group memberships, educational institutions, and professional associations. The notion of privacy holds less significance, as Turks commonly lean toward collaborative dynamics within their social circles encompassing family and friends. However, it’s worth noting that inter-group competition can be notably intense despite the cooperative tendencies observed.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">In the context of Turkish society, women typically find avenues for expressing anger within the confines of same-sex friendships and familial bonds. These channels are considered acceptable, as is the case when addressing individuals of lower social strata. However, it is important to acknowledge that women often encounter constraints in openly venting their frustrations toward their spouses or individuals occupying higher positions of influence.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Engaging in physical contact such as touching, hand-holding, and gentle patting is considered socially acceptable among individuals of the same sex in friendships, as well as between individuals of opposite sexes who are in romantic relationships. Similarly, there exists a closer personal space between same-sex friends compared to opposite-sex partners, with physical proximity being esteemed as an indicator of emotional intimacy. <emphasis role="bold">Touch, when necessary, is allowed and expected from healthcare providers. However, strict Muslims may not shake hands or touch members of the opposite sex, especially if they are not related.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Eye contact serves as a means of conveying respect in Turkish culture. In the presence of individuals holding higher social status, it is customary to maintain intermittent eye contact to signal attentiveness. Nonetheless, it is important to exercise discretion, as extended or sustained eye contact can be construed as impolite or even suggestive of flirtatious behavior. <emphasis role="bold">Maintain eye contact with patients, demonstrating respect and truthfulness.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">In Turkish culture, a prevailing inclination toward formal attire is evident. On social occasions, men often opt for suits instead of more casual sports jackets and slacks. Women, however, tend to embrace modest clothing choices, favoring skirts and dresses over trousers. It is noteworthy that more conservative Muslim women might adhere to particularly modest clothing and may use black or colorful printed scarves to cover their heads. However, it’s important to acknowledge the evolving nature of fashion trends. Among the younger demographic, denim jeans and casual attire are progressively gaining traction, particularly for less formal gatherings. This shift underscores the dynamic interplay between tradition and contemporary preferences within Turkish dress codes. <emphasis role="bold">Expect a wide variety of dress among Turks, depending on religiosity, acculturation, and age.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Turkish individuals commonly exhibit a proclivity for openly expressing a range of emotions, including happiness, disgust, approval, disapproval, and sadness, through readily discernible facial expressions and gestures. The negation “no” is frequently conveyed through the raising of eyebrows or a subtle lifting of the chin, often accompanied by a sharp snapping or “tsk” sound. An emblem of appreciation involves bringing together the fingertips and thumb, followed by a kissing gesture, which is frequently employed to convey gratitude for food. These distinctive nonverbal cues and gestures form an integral aspect of Turkish communication norms.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Maintaining a meticulously clean home is a source of pride within Turkish culture, underscored by the customary practice of removing shoes upon entering. It is commonplace for Turkish hosts in both Türkiye and, to a significant extent, the United States and some other countries, to provide guests with slippers. Irrespective of footwear, revealing the sole of one’s foot is deemed disrespectful. Additionally, women are expected to observe modest sitting postures, typically maintaining knees together and refraining from crossing them. These cultural norms reflect the value placed on cleanliness, hospitality, and decorum in Turkish society. <emphasis role="bold">Home healthcare providers should look for cues and ask if they should remove their shoes when entering the home of a Turkish family.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">In the realm of business relationships and healthcare appointments, the significance of punctuality is steadily growing within the Turkish American community. <emphasis role="bold">Explain the necessity of being punctual for healthcare appointments.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Titles serve as essential markers of respect and social status within Turkish culture. When addressing individuals, even those unknown, it is customary to employ their relevant titles, such as Bey (Mr.), Hanim (Mrs., Miss, or Ms.), <emphasis>Doktor</emphasis>, or <emphasis>Profesör</emphasis>. The same principle extends to familial interactions, where specific titles reflecting relationships are employed. For instance, terms like agbi (older brother or older close male friend), amca (uncle or elderly male relative or stranger), abla (older sister or older close female friend), teyze (maternal aunt or older female relative or older female stranger), and yenge (wife of a brother or paternal uncle) are utilized. This practice underscores the importance of demonstrating respect and acknowledging social dynamics through appropriate address. <emphasis role="bold">Greet patients formally with their title or Mr., Mrs., or Ms.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0033s0001s0002" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">33.1.2 </emphasis> Family Roles and Organization</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">In a highly traditional Turkish household, the father assumes a role of unequivocal authority. However, within families embracing less traditional values, a notable shift toward spousal equality becomes evident, particularly in nuclear family structures where the wife possesses a strong educational background and is engaged in professional pursuits outside the home. Notably, contemporary women in Türkiye tend to exhibit a greater degree of Westernization in comparison to certain counterparts within Middle Eastern or Muslim societies. This variance underscores the evolving dynamics shaping gender roles and cultural influences in modern Türkiye. <emphasis role="bold">Ascertain the family spokesperson before eliciting health-care decisions. Accept family decision-making patterns without judgment.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Upon entering the school system, children are met with expectations to dedicate themselves to their studies, demonstrate respect, and adhere to the guidance of their elders, including older siblings. Conventional norms dictate that children refrain from engaging in disruptive behavior or expressing defiance toward their superiors. It’s worth noting that traditional views permit a degree of light corporal punishment as a means of discipline, although practices in this regard are undergoing change due to evolving societal perspectives. <emphasis role="bold">Explain the legalities of child abuse in the United States and elsewhere.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Circumcision stands as a significant rite of passage for male children within Turkish culture. This occasion is marked by familial celebration involving the extended family and includes the bestowing of gifts upon the newly circumcised boys. While the traditional practice allows for circumcision up to approximately 12 years of age, contemporary customs are shifting toward hospital-based procedures shortly after birth. This evolution reflects the intersection of tradition and modern medical practices in the Turkish context.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Sexual interaction is notably discouraged among unmarried youth in Turkish society, with a particular emphasis on preserving chastity, especially in the case of women for whom virginity holds substantial cultural significance.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">While financial self-sufficiency holds significance within Turkish culture, the pursuit of independence from the family unit is not strongly promoted. Adult offspring, particularly sons, continue to play a vital role in their parent’s lives, and it is anticipated that they will assume caregiving responsibilities for their elders in later years. This emphasis underscores the enduring familial bonds and intergenerational obligations within Turkish society.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Parents or other family members are often consulted before major decisions are made.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para ParaOneEmphasisChild">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Facilitating compliance with health prescriptions and health education can be effectively achieved through the strategic organization of a family conference led by a designated family spokesperson. This approach proves advantageous in fostering understanding and garnering support for recommended health practices within the family unit.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Among young individuals, residing within their parental home is customary until marriage unless educational pursuits or professional obligations necessitate alternative living arrangements. While arranged marriages persist within certain segments of Turkish society, this practice is comparatively less prevalent among Turkish individuals residing in Western countries.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Individuals are ingrained with a sense of responsibility to care for their parents when the need for assistance arises. The active involvement of grandparents in the upbringing of their grandchildren is pronounced, particularly when they share a household. This intergenerational dynamic underscores the pivotal role of family support in Turkish culture.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Within numerous Turkish families, the extended family encompasses aunts, uncles, cousins, and in-laws. This expansive network fosters a cooperative dynamic that extends to diverse aspects of life, encompassing the sharing of responsibilities such as child care, labor, and sustenance as circumstances require. This collaborative ethos underscores the significance of familial bonds in Turkish cultural traditions. <emphasis role="bold">Use the extended family arrangement for health teaching and home care.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">The prevalence of divorce is on the rise, although it continues to carry a certain social stigma, particularly for women. The act of divorcing remains culturally unfavorable. In cases of widowhood, there exists a customary practice of extended family support, where the deceased husband’s family assumes responsibility for the care of the widow. Depending on factors such as age and socioeconomic status, widows may have the opportunity to remarry, reflecting the flexibility within this traditional framework.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">The acceptance of homosexuality in Turkish society is gradually emerging, albeit with a certain degree of reservation. Many Turks exhibit a reluctance to align themselves with the gay community openly. There exists a noticeable hesitancy among individuals to establish affiliations with this demographic, reflecting the evolving but still somewhat distant reception of homosexuality within the cultural context. <emphasis role="bold">Do not disclose same-sex relationships to family members or others.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0033s0001s0003" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">33.1.3 </emphasis> Workforce Issues</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Türkiye is characterized by a culture that prioritizes group dynamics, and this orientation often extends to the workplace, which tends to emphasize a team-oriented approach.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">The Turkish cultural inclination toward relationship-oriented interactions can result in a reliance on personal connections and networks to achieve tasks. The process of cultivating relationships and networks, while intrinsic to Turkish norms, might be perceived as nepotism or excessive socializing from an American standpoint. <emphasis role="bold">Orient nurses to the Turkish perspective on relationships and the Turkish perspective of relationship to American nurses.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Within the Turkish work environment, there exists an anticipation for a hierarchical relationship between supervisors and subordinates. The practice of delivering criticism indirectly is not only customary but also valued, as it serves to “save face.” It’s important to note that openly critiquing a Turkish individual, especially in a public setting, can be deeply offensive and detrimental to interpersonal dynamics. <emphasis role="bold">Do not criticize Turks in front of other employees.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">They may be reticent about asking questions for fear of exposing a lack of knowledge. <emphasis role="bold">Ask employees to demonstrate a procedure to ensure understanding.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Turks handle differences of opinion in a brisk and clear-cut manner.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Because most Turkish immigrants speak English, language barriers in the workplace may be only subtle.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Turkish cultural norms dictate that confrontational interactions conducted in an assertive manner have the potential to erode relationships. Consequently, conflict resolution predominantly revolves around collaborative approaches, supported by elements of compromise and assertiveness. Compromise and avoidance tend to manifest among peers, whereas accommodation behaviors are more commonly employed when interacting with superiors. This nuanced conflict resolution framework reflects the cultural emphasis on maintaining harmonious interpersonal connections.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Türkiye is recognized for its significant power distance, reflecting the substantial psychological and emotional gap that often exists between superiors and subordinates. The culture places a strong emphasis on respecting authority, resulting in a centralized administrative structure and an authoritarian leadership approach that characterizes various facets of Turkish society.</para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0033s0001s0004" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">33.1.4 </emphasis> Biocultural Ecology</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">The Turkish population is a mosaic in terms of appearance, complexion, and coloration. Appearances range from light-skinned with blue or green eyes to olive or darker skin tones with brown eyes. Mongolian spots, usually found at or near the sacrum, are common among Turkish babies and should not be confused with bruising.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Table <emphasis role="InternalRef">
                        <link linkend="ch0033s0001ta01">33.1</link>
                     </emphasis> lists commonly occurring health conditions for Turks in three categories: lifestyle, environment, and genetics. See Chap. <emphasis role="ExternalRef">
                        <ulink url="ch0002#ch0002">
                           <emphasis role="RefSource">2</emphasis>
                        </ulink>
                     </emphasis>.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Endemic goiter associated with iodine deficiency is a major health problem in Türkiye despite iodine prophylaxis. <emphasis role="bold">Screen newer immigrants for helminthiasis and goiter.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para ParaOneEmphasisChild">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Assess for lactose intolerance as part of the intake interviews, and help patients identify alternative sources of calcium. Assess Turkish patients for β-thalassemia before prescribing medications.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Turks in Türkiye have high rates of occupational injuries. <emphasis role="bold">Provide education regarding safety issues in occupational health.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Turks are at high-risk for multiple cancers because of the Chernobyl accident in the Soviet Union in 1986; this includes children born after this period as well.</para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
            <table id="ch0033s0001ta01">
               <title>
                  <emphasis role="CaptionNumber">Table 33.1</emphasis> Health conditions common to Turks</title>
               <tgroup cols="2">
                  <colspec colname="c1" colnum="1"/>
                  <colspec colname="c2" colnum="2"/>
                  <tbody>
