         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0033s0001s0005" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">33.1.5 </emphasis> High-Risk Health Behaviors</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Cigarette smoking is widespread in Türkiye and tends to start at an early age. Türkiye is a major producer of tobacco in the world. <emphasis role="bold">Encourage patients to cease smoking and help them access smoking cessation programs. Start teaching the hazards of smoking in elementary school.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Turks tend to consume less alcohol than Americans or Europeans, perhaps as a result of the Muslim culture that discourages more than moderate alcohol use.</para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0033s0001s0006" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">33.1.6 </emphasis> Nutrition</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Food preferences in Türkiye encompass a diverse range of options, often contributing to a well-rounded and health-conscious diet. Turkish cuisine, while not excessively spicy, is distinguished by meticulous and skillful preparation. The culinary tradition places great value on both the aesthetic presentation and the nutritional quality of dishes.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Although a typical family dinner in Türkiye might exhibit simplicity, guests are commonly treated to an abundant selection of dishes. The prevailing sentiment is that more food signifies generosity leading to instances where dinner guests are presented with a profusion of culinary offerings. This approach sometimes results in guests finding it challenging to consume everything on their plates, as Turkish hostesses are inclined to offer replacements for consumed items repeatedly. In accordance with etiquette, polite guests typically decline the initial offer, signifying a cultural practice rooted in hospitality and respect.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Breakfast is typically a simple meal of <emphasis>beyaz peynir</emphasis> (white feta cheese), olives, tomatoes, eggs, cucumbers, toast, jam, honey, and Turkish tea. Turks typically eat dinner at about 8 p.m. <emphasis role="bold">Take mealtimes into consideration when teaching Turkish patients about medication therapies.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">The spectrum of soups in Turkish cuisine spans from delicately flavored options to more substantial choices. Hors d’oeuvres encompass a wide array of petite dishes, ranging from hot to cold, including items such as olive oil-stuffed grape leaves, olives, Circassian chicken with walnut sauce, dried mackerel, roasted chickpeas, and crispy fried savory cheese pastries. These appetizers are frequently complemented by <emphasis>rakí</emphasis>, a traditional anisette liquor derived from grapes, typically served over ice with water and sipped at a leisurely pace. This culinary tradition reflects the rich diversity and meticulous attention to detail inherent in Turkish gastronomy.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Salads in Turkish cuisine consist of a medley of fresh ingredients such as lettuce, tomatoes, cucumbers, and onions, often combined with raw vegetables. These salads are typically dressed with olive oil and either lemon juice or vinegar. Turkish culinary practices often involve the preparation of meat in modest portions, often accompanied by various vegetables, potatoes, or rice. Notable dishes within Turkish gastronomy encompass <emphasis>köfte</emphasis>, which are small, well-seasoned meatballs, as well as <emphasis>kebabs</emphasis> consisting of skewered beef or lamb complemented by an assortment of vegetables. This culinary selection is emblematic of the meticulous blending of flavors and textures that characterizes Turkish cuisine.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Yogurt, a culinary creation attributed to the Turkish people, holds a fundamental position within the Turkish diet. Its consumption is often integrated into meals served at elevated temperatures rather than being relegated to a cold breakfast option. This cultural approach to yogurt underscores its versatile role as a complement to various dishes, emblematic of the inventive and diverse culinary traditions of Türkiye.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Rice and <emphasis>börek</emphasis> are important parts of Turkish culinary tradition. <emphasis>Börek</emphasis> is made by wrapping <emphasis>yufka</emphasis> (thin sheets of flour-based dough) around meat, cheese, or spinach and then frying or baking until the dough is flaky.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Turkish desserts can be classified into four distinct categories: opulent and sugary pastries, exemplified by <emphasis>baklava</emphasis>; creamy and indulgent puddings; cooked fruits offering a sweet profile; and the inclusion of fresh fruits. A customary practice involves concluding meals with a selection of fresh fruits, often accompanied by coffee or tea. This dessert tradition exemplifies the multifaceted nature of Turkish cuisine, where a diversity of flavors and textures are harmoniously integrated into culinary offerings.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Renowned for its robust and sweet profile, Turkish <emphasis>kahve</emphasis>, a dark and dense coffee, holds a distinguished place in the culinary landscape. <emphasis>Ayran</emphasis>, a blend of yogurt and milk, is the prevailing cold beverage in Türkiye, enjoyed by individuals of all ages. It’s notable that the Islamic faith mandates abstaining from pork consumption and alcohol consumption, but adherence varies based on individual levels of religious observance. The diversity in practice reflects the nuanced relationship between faith and cultural practices within the Muslim community.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para ParaOneEmphasisChild">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Given the diversity among food options in the United States and elsewhere, provide dietary counseling according to the individual’s unique food choices and practices.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Ramazan</emphasis>, the Islamic tradition known as <emphasis role="bold">Ramadan</emphasis> in Arabic countries, entails a month-long fasting practice observed by devout Muslims across the globe. Throughout the course of Ramazan, individuals refrain from eating or drinking from sunrise until sunset. The extent of adherence to this practice varies considerably, ranging from those who do not observe it to those who meticulously adhere to its tenets. This variance reflects the diverse spectrum of observance within the global Muslim community.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Within the Sunni Muslim tradition, the commencement of Ramazan observance occurs at the onset of puberty. Some adherents hold the belief that women have an obligation to fast even during pregnancy and the postnatal phase. In contrast, Alevi Muslims do not impose fasting obligations on either gender. Typically, pregnant and postpartum women, individuals traveling, and those dealing with illness are exempt from fasting, although there may be an expectation to compensate for missed days at a later point, thereby illustrating the nuanced approach to fasting regulations across different situations within the Islamic framework. <emphasis role="bold">Health teaching strategies for Turks in America and elsewhere should include the recognition and prevention of dehydration, bloating, constipation, and fatigue during periods of Ramazan fasting (see Chap.</emphasis>
                     <emphasis role="ExternalRef">
                        <ulink url="ch0008#ch0008">
                           <emphasis role="RefSource">
                              <emphasis role="bold">8</emphasis>
                           </emphasis>
                        </ulink>
                     </emphasis>
                     <emphasis role="bold">).</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Fasting can potentially lead to an array of digestive issues and pose health risks, particularly in the case of pregnant or postnatal women and their infants. The physiological changes associated with fasting may jeopardize the well-being of both the mother and the child, underscoring the importance of considering individual health conditions and circumstances when observing fasting practices within specific religious contexts. <emphasis role="bold">Provide factual information regarding fasting and the potential effect on some health conditions.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Molasses, <emphasis>baklava</emphasis>, <emphasis>lokum</emphasis> (Turkish delight), tahini, honey and nuts, and raisins are believed to increase strength and sexual vigor.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Fruits, especially bananas, oranges, tangerines, and apples, are brought to convalescing people, helping them to regain their strength and aiding in the healing process.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Chicken soup is a common remedy for cold and flu symptoms. An <emphasis>ebe</emphasis> (a traditional Türkiye midwife) relies on various herbs and home remedies to heal patients. <emphasis>Ebegömeci</emphasis> (a spinach-like leaf or herb) may be prepared for topical or oral use to treat inflammation, infection, and sometimes infertility.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Tea, cinnamon, hot water with sugar, ginger, mint, and various roots are used separately or in various combinations to treat rheumatism, low blood pressure, intestinal gas, colds, and flu. Nettles may be used topically for rheumatism, arthritis, and varicose veins.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">A traditional folk remedy for diabetes involves the process of boiling olive leaves and subsequently refrigerating the resulting infusion before consuming the extracted juice.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">
                     <emphasis>Lapa</emphasis>, a watery rice mixture with a gruel-like texture, or a boiled potato may be used to treat diarrhea and is followed by yogurt to replace the natural flora of the intestines.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para ParaOneEmphasisChild">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Ask Turkish patients if they are using traditional dietary practices and incorporate them into prescription therapies. Because malnutrition may be a significant problem among economically disadvantaged Turks immigrating to the United States and elsewhere, consider extensive nutritional assessments for more recent immigrants.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0033s0001s0007" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">33.1.7 </emphasis> Pregnancy and Childbearing Practices</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Until the 1960s, the sale of contraceptives and the dissemination of birth control education were prohibited in Türkiye. The legality of abortion and sterilization, with exceptions for medical necessities, remained restricted until 1983. Presently, prevalent contraception methods among Turkish women encompass withdrawal, utilization of intrauterine devices, and the use of birth control pills. This historical progression reflects the evolving landscape of reproductive health practices within Turkish society. <emphasis role="bold">Given the history of family planning in Türkiye, be open to culturally congruent ways to discussions of family planning with Turkish people in the United States and elsewhere.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Motherhood holds a position of considerable reverence within Turkish culture, and pregnant women are afforded extensive care and comfort, often accommodating their cravings. Pregnant individuals are commonly encouraged to maintain their routine activities or work as long as they feel at ease. This approach underscores the cultural esteem for motherhood and the collective effort to ensure the well-being of expectant mothers.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Many pregnant women take prenatal vitamins, drink a lot of milk, and apply salves such as Vaseline to avoid stretch marks. Light exercise, such as walking, is encouraged, but weather conditions often hamper such efforts because Turks generally avoid wet or cold weather, fearing its ill effects on one’s health.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Most Turks prefer hospitals for physician-assisted child delivery. The husband and the birth mother’s father may be present during the birthing process. Expressions of discomfort and pain are quite acceptable.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">The postpartum period can last up to 40 days. Light exercise is encouraged during this period, and bathing, an important part of the Muslim tradition, is strongly encouraged.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">A distinct dietary item known as “ <emphasis>lousalik</emphasis>” is customarily offered to postpartum women. <emphasis>Lousalik</emphasis> is a sweet, sherbet-like substance created by dissolving <emphasis>lousalik</emphasis> beads in hot water. This carbohydrate-rich preparation is designed to enhance the woman’s vitality during the postpartum phase. Hot soups and fluid consumption, including milk, feature prominently in the diets of postpartum women, particularly those breastfeeding. The practice of breastfeeding is highly esteemed among the majority of Turkish individuals, and while it is commonly embraced, it is typically approached with modesty. This cultural perspective reflects the significance attributed to maternal health and child-rearing practices. <emphasis role="bold">Encourage the incorporation of nonharmful postpartum practices with Western interventions.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">A customary practice involves the placement of a small blue bead, known as a “nazar boncuk,” on the left shoulder of a child. This bead is believed to offer protection against the perceived malevolent influence of the “evil eye,” specifically guarding against the influence of the evil angel purportedly whispering into the child’s left ear. Additionally, other traditional safeguards include positioning iron beneath the baby’s mattress as a precaution against anemia. Likewise, tying a yellow ribbon to the crib is thought to avert jaundice, while affixing a red bow serves as a symbolic countermeasure to deflect any potential envious or negative energies. These practices reflect the cultural significance attributed to safeguarding infants from potential harm and ill intentions. <emphasis role="bold">Do not remove protective beads or ribbons from the infant’s bedside.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Swaddling, a common practice, has been linked to congenital hip dislocation, pneumonia, and upper respiratory infections among young infants. <emphasis role="bold">Explain the harmful effect of swaddling.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0033s0001s0008" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">33.1.8 </emphasis> Death Rituals</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Cremation is not commonly practiced among Turkish Muslims due to their religious conviction that the body should remain intact. Following the passing of an individual, a ritualistic washing of the body takes place, after which it is enshrouded in a white sheet. This practice adheres to the cultural and religious importance placed on preserving the sanctity of the deceased individual’s physical form.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Muslim Turks are placed in the grave, with the right side of the body facing Mecca.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">The traditional mourning period is 40 days, during which traditionally, those attending the ceremony wear black clothes or a black scarf.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">While Muslim Turks hold a belief in the afterlife, the passing of an individual is consistently marked by profound sorrow and mourning. A common expression of condolences to those bereaved is “ <emphasis>Basınız sağ olsun</emphasis>,” which translates to “May your head be healthy.” This sentiment carries the hope that the mourning individual will not be overcome by grief. This cultural practice reflects the cultural and emotional sensitivity that surrounds the topic of death within Turkish society.</para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0033s0001s0009" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">33.1.9 </emphasis> Spirituality</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">The predominant religious affiliation among Turks is Sunni Islam, while a minority belongs to the Alevi Muslim group. Notably, a substantial proportion of Turkish immigrants to Western countries tend to adhere to a more moderate interpretation of Islam. This religious diversity among Turkish expatriates underscores the varying degrees of religious observance and beliefs within this demographic, reflecting the broader spectrum of religious practices observed by Turks residing outside their homeland.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Traditional prayer is practiced five times each day and can take place anywhere, as long as one is facing the holy city of Mecca. A special small rug called <emphasis>seccade</emphasis> is used for praying in places other than the <emphasis>
                        <emphasis role="bold">cami</emphasis>
                     </emphasis>, mosque. When entering the <emphasis>cami</emphasis>, shoes are always removed, and women must cover their heads. Men and women go to separate parts of the <emphasis>cami</emphasis> for prayer. One prepares for prayer by ritual cleansing, which, at minimum, includes washing the face, ears, nostrils, neck, hands to the elbow, and feet and legs to the knee, three times each.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para ParaOneEmphasisChild">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Caregivers may need to make special arrangements so that Muslims can practice their religious obligations when they are in a healthcare facility.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Spiritual leaders or healers are sought for assistance with relationships or emotional problems. A <emphasis>muska</emphasis>, a paper inscribed by a <emphasis>hoca</emphasis> (an alderman) with a prayer in Arabic, is wrapped in fabric and hidden in the home or worn by the person seeking help. <emphasis>Turbe</emphasis> and <emphasis>yatir</emphasis> are the practice of going to the graves of scholars to pray about wishes, mental or emotional problems, or fertility problems. <emphasis>
                        <emphasis role="bold">Tesbih</emphasis>
                     </emphasis> (small beads traditionally used for praying) now take a more secular meaning and are often referred to as “worry beads.” <emphasis role="bold">Religious or folk items should not be removed because they provide comfort for the patient and removal may increase anxiety.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0033s0001s0010" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">33.1.10 </emphasis> Health-Care Practices</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">While the majority of Turks predominantly seek health and curative care from Western medicine provided by well-trained professionals, vestiges of traditional beliefs persist in parallel. A prevalent viewpoint attributing the origins of illness to imbalances of hot and cold elements endures within the cultural framework. For instance, ailments like diarrhea are ascribed to an excess of cold or heat, whereas conditions such as pneumonia are associated with extreme cold. This coexistence of modern medical practices and enduring traditional beliefs underscores the complex healthcare landscape in Turkish society.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Many Turks have a traditional fatalistic worldview, which is more common among those living in extended households who believe “You cannot change what God has written.” <emphasis role="bold">Incorporate factual information for the entire family regarding disease causation and treatment in patient education.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">In the context of terminal illness, it is customary in Turkish medical practices to withhold the full severity of the condition from patients. This approach stems from the belief that imparting such information could potentially diminish hope, motivation, and the vital energy required for healing. Additionally, the disclosure of a terminal diagnosis might intensify patient anxieties pertaining to mortality and the impact on their loved ones. This approach is aligned with the perspective that the ultimate outcome is beyond human control and rests with divine will. This blend of cultural and spiritual considerations underscores the nuanced manner in which medical information is conveyed within the Turkish healthcare framework. <emphasis role="bold">Take cues from the patient and discuss the patient’s condition with the family before disclosing the severity to the patient.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Within Turkish households, women typically assume the role of primary caregivers for the ailing. Moreover, pivotal healthcare decisions often rest in the hands of the individual held in the highest esteem for their level of education. This arrangement underscores the gender-specific care-taking dynamics and hierarchical decision-making process within the context of health and well-being in Turkish society. <emphasis role="bold">Determine the family spokesperson for decision-making on health issues and incorporate group interventions whenever possible.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Türkiye demonstrates elevated rates of over-the-counter antibiotic and painkiller utilization, with aspirin often being embraced as a universal remedy for diverse afflictions, including gastric discomfort. A notable trend involves individuals, particularly those encountering financial constraints with regard to accessing medical services, frequently seeking guidance from pharmacists prior to consulting a physician. This practice reflects the significant role of pharmacists in the healthcare field and underscores the broader healthcare dynamics, including self-care and affordability considerations, prevalent within Turkish society. <emphasis role="bold">Assess Turkish patients for their use of over-the-counter medications to prevent conflicting or potentiating effects with prescription medications.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">The belief in the “evil eye” holds significant cultural prominence within Turkish society. An inherent caution exists against excessively extolling one’s state of health, as it is thought that doing so may inadvertently attract misfortune through others’ envious gazes. This sentiment is so deeply ingrained that even taxi drivers and medical practitioners revere the protective power of the “ <emphasis>nazar boncuk</emphasis>,” a blue bead utilized as a shield against the malevolent effects of the evil eye. When discussing ailments, individuals consciously avoid employing themselves or others as examples, lest such descriptions inadvertently invite affliction upon the person being discussed. This intricate interplay between cultural beliefs and health-related conversations demonstrates the enduring influence of traditional superstitions within Turkish cultural norms.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">The practice of using “kolonya” (cologne) is a cherished tradition that transcends religious and secular boundaries within Turkish culture. Stemming from a foundation of reverence for cleanliness, this practice involves applying cologne to the hands of guests both before and after meals, offering a dual benefit of sanitization and infusing a pleasant lemon fragrance. Additionally, inhaling the aroma from a cloth or handkerchief imbued with a cologne is employed as a remedy for alleviating motion sickness. Notably, within medical settings, patients may extend the gesture of offering cologne to physicians or nurses prior to undergoing an examination. This multifaceted utilization of cologne underscores its integral role in Turkish customs, blending hygiene, comfort, and cultural expressions of hospitality. <emphasis role="bold">Respect this custom as appropriate.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Other home remedies include using rubbing alcohol or a wet cloth to bring down a fever and warming the back to treat coughing.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Turkish culture allows freedom to express pain through either emotional outbursts or verbal complaints. <emphasis role="bold">Accept a wide range of pain expression among Turkish patients.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Although stigma is attached to mental illness, many families seek treatment or care for the patient at home. The most common reasons given for mental illness include discord among family members, marital and love problems, gossip, and other familial problems. Social causes include financial inadequacies, societal disorders, and a “struggle with life.” Men more frequently blame social causes for mental illness, and women often give psychological causes. <emphasis role="bold">Address somatization among Turkish patients with mental health concerns, and encourage the expression of their feelings. Incorporate group interventions whenever possible.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Within the context of hospitalization, the term “ <emphasis>refakatçı</emphasis>” pertains to the individual who remains overnight with the patient, offering indispensable emotional and physical support and solace. Demonstrating care and compassion serves to alleviate apprehensions and diminish feelings of isolation experienced by the patient. Additionally, family members may take on responsibilities such as aiding with bathing and tending to other physical requirements. Emphasizing a well-rounded, nutritious diet is deemed crucial for the process of recuperation, with a common practice being the provision of home-cooked meals brought from outside the hospital setting. This comprehensive approach underscores the multifaceted nature of Turkish healthcare customs, intertwining emotional well-being, familial involvement, and dietary considerations in the realm of patient care. <emphasis role="bold">Encourage family-assisted care, and allow families to provide homemade foods.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">While blood transfusions are gaining acceptance, Turkish people usually prefer to receive blood from family members. Muslims traditionally prefer that the body remain intact after death, a belief that may conflict with organ donation.</para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0033s0001s0011" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">33.1.11 </emphasis> Health-Care Providers</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Although Turkish people are inclined toward Western health-seeking behaviors, medical care tends to be holistic. Great value is placed on emotional well-being, especially as it affects physical well-being. Physicians may be “adopted” as members of their patient’s families, and it is common to give gifts (usually food) to the physician as an expression of gratitude.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Generally, treating someone of the opposite sex is not an issue among Turks. <emphasis role="bold">Ask each patient for preference on gender issues in health care.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Physicians, and to a lesser extent, nurses and midwives, have historically been held in very high esteem. Patients rarely question the authority of physicians, but the notion of obtaining a second opinion is gaining popularity.</para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
      </sect1>
      <sect1 id="ch0033s0002" role="Heading">
         <sect1info>
            <risinfo>
               <booktitle>Handbook for Culturally Competent Care</booktitle>
               <isbn>1316139783031</isbn>
               <chapternumber>33</chapternumber>
               <chapterid>ch0033</chapterid>
               <chaptertitle>33. People of Turkish Heritage</chaptertitle>
               <authorgroup>
                  <author>
                     <personname>
                        <firstname>Eric A.</firstname>
                        <surname>Fenkl</surname>
                     </personname>
                  </author>
                  <author>
                     <personname>
                        <firstname>Larry D.</firstname>
                        <surname>Purnell</surname>
                     </personname>
                  </author>
               </authorgroup>
               <publisher>
                  <publishername>Springer International Publishing</publishername>
               </publisher>
               <pubdate>2024</pubdate>
            </risinfo>
