   <chapter id="ch0034" label="34">
      <title>34. People of Ukrainian Heritage</title>
      <sect1 id="ch0034s0004">
         <sect1info>
            <risinfo>
               <booktitle>Handbook for Culturally Competent Care</booktitle>
               <isbn>1316139783031</isbn>
               <chapternumber>34</chapternumber>
               <chapterid>ch0034</chapterid>
               <chaptertitle>34. People of Ukrainian Heritage</chaptertitle>
               <authorgroup>
                  <author>
                     <personname>
                        <firstname>Eric A.</firstname>
                        <surname>Fenkl</surname>
                     </personname>
                  </author>
                  <author>
                     <personname>
                        <firstname>Larry D.</firstname>
                        <surname>Purnell</surname>
                     </personname>
                  </author>
               </authorgroup>
               <publisher>
                  <publishername>Springer International Publishing</publishername>
               </publisher>
               <pubdate>2024</pubdate>
            </risinfo>
            <primaryauthor>
               <personname>
                  <firstname>Eric A.</firstname>
                  <surname>Fenkl</surname>
               </personname>
            </primaryauthor>
         </sect1info>
         <title>34. People of Ukrainian Heritage</title>
         <para role="ChapterCopyright">© The Author(s), under exclusive license to Springer Nature Switzerland AG 2024</para>
         <para role="ContextInformationAuthorEditorNames">E. A. Fenkl, L. D. Purnell<emphasis role="CollaboratorDesignation"> (eds.)</emphasis>
         </para>
         <para role="ContextInformationBookTitles">
            <emphasis role="BookTitle">Handbook for Culturally Competent Care</emphasis>
         </para>
         <para role="ChapterDOI">
            <ulink url="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-031-70492-5_34">https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-031-70492-5_34</ulink>
         </para>
         <para role="AuthorGroup">
            <emphasis role="Author">
               <emphasis role="AuthorName">Tatayana Maltseva</emphasis>
               <superscript>
                  <link linkend="ch0034">1</link>
               </superscript> and </emphasis>
            <emphasis role="Author">
               <emphasis role="AuthorName">Irina Rozenfeld</emphasis>
               <superscript>
                  <link linkend="ch0034">2</link>
               </superscript>
            </emphasis>
         </para>
         <para role="AffiliationText">Nicole Wertheim College of Nursing and Health Sciences, Florida International University, Miami, FL, USA</para>
         <para role="AffiliationText">Dr. Kiran C. Patel College of Osteopathic Medicine, Nova University, Fort Lauderdale, FL, USA</para>
         <para role="Contact">
            <emphasis role="AuthorName">Tatayana Maltseva</emphasis> (Corresponding author)<?lb?>
            <emphasis role="ContactType">Email: </emphasis>
            <ulink url="mailto:bogopolt@fiu.edu">bogopolt@fiu.edu</ulink>
         </para>
         <para role="Contact">
            <emphasis role="AuthorName">Irina Rozenfeld</emphasis><?lb?>
            <emphasis role="ContactType">Email: </emphasis>
            <ulink url="mailto:rozenfel@nova.edu">rozenfel@nova.edu</ulink>
         </para>
         <para role="keywords">Heritage, Family roles, Spirituality, Health behavior, War</para>
      </sect1>
      <sect1 id="ch0034s0001" role="Heading">
         <sect1info>
            <risinfo>
               <booktitle>Handbook for Culturally Competent Care</booktitle>
               <isbn>1316139783031</isbn>
               <chapternumber>34</chapternumber>
               <chapterid>ch0034</chapterid>
               <chaptertitle>34. People of Ukrainian Heritage</chaptertitle>
               <authorgroup>
                  <author>
                     <personname>
                        <firstname>Eric A.</firstname>
                        <surname>Fenkl</surname>
                     </personname>
                  </author>
                  <author>
                     <personname>
                        <firstname>Larry D.</firstname>
                        <surname>Purnell</surname>
                     </personname>
                  </author>
               </authorgroup>
               <publisher>
                  <publishername>Springer International Publishing</publishername>
               </publisher>
               <pubdate>2024</pubdate>
            </risinfo>
            <primaryauthor>
               <personname>
                  <firstname>Eric A.</firstname>
                  <surname>Fenkl</surname>
               </personname>
            </primaryauthor>
         </sect1info>
         <title>
            <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">34.1 </emphasis> Overview and Heritage</title>
         <para role="Para">Ukraine is the second-largest European country by area in Eastern Europe. Ethnic Ukrainians belong to the Slavic nationality group. The capital of Ukraine is Kyiv. The national groups residing in Ukraine include Ukrainians, Russians, Belarusians, Bulgarians, Crimean Tatars, Moldovans, Jews, and Hungarians. Russians account for about a sixth of Ukraine’s population. Most of the people in the Crimean Peninsula are of Russian ethnicity. Ukraine is one of the world’s leading farming regions. During A. D. 800s, Kyiv became the center of a Slavic state that modern historians call Kievan Rus (also spelled <emphasis>Kyivan Rus)</emphasis>. Parts of Ukraine were under Polish, Lithuanian, and Austrian control until the late 1700s, when almost all of Ukraine came under Russian control. In 1922, Ukraine became one of the four original republics of the Soviet Union (USSR), but in 1991, Ukraine declared its political independence from the USSR. Ukraine has a significant history of movement for national independence with strong aspirations to join the European Union in recent years. During the post-Soviet period, some Ukrainian citizens left the country for economic reasons and have been working abroad and supporting families at home. In 2014, Maidan Revolution in Kyiv led to the removal of the Ukrainian president from office and the beginning of civilian unrest in the Eastern part of the country and Crimea. In February 2022, the Russia–Ukraine war started, contributing to millions of Ukrainian citizens escaping war zone and significant number of citizens volunteered joining military units on the front line or at the local territorial defense units. A new wave of Ukrainian immigrants to the United States comprised of younger generation Ukrainians who are usually well-educated or have good vocational skills. Many are proficient in English and can find gainful employment upon arrival in the United States. Recently immigrated Ukrainians may have higher level of medical and psychological needs due to exposure to war (Popova and Shevel, <emphasis role="CitationRef">
               <link linkend="ch0034s0003bib08">2024</link>
            </emphasis>).</para>
         <sect2 id="ch0034s0001s0001" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">34.1.1 </emphasis> Communications</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Ukrainians tend to be relatively straightforward and use a direct communication style. They expect others to be clear and open when expressing their opinions. They may not be overly polite or use innocent words discussing sensitive topics. While being direct, they may in some cases use indirect communication. When discussing sensitive or confrontational topics, they may use euphemisms instead of addressing the issue.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Ukrainians may use <emphasis role="bold">nonverbal communications</emphasis> via facial expressions, gestures, and eye contact to convey emotions and meanings. <emphasis role="bold">Maintaining eye contact during a conversation is generally seen as a sign of attentiveness and sincerity</emphasis>. Ukrainians may avoid direct eye contact in communication with authorities.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Ukrainians often show respect for authority figures. They may use titles and honorifics when addressing superiors in hierarchical organizational settings. It is a sign of respect to address older person by first and middle name.</para>
                  <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkDash">
                     <listitem>
                        <para role="Para">
                           <emphasis role="bold">Personal Relationships</emphasis>: Ukrainians often prefer to do business with people they know and trust. “<emphasis>
                              <emphasis role="bold">Small Talk</emphasis>
                           </emphasis>” or polite inquiries about one’s health, family, and general well-being are common to build rapport.</para>
                     </listitem>
                     <listitem>
                        <para role="Para">
                           <emphasis role="bold">Language</emphasis>: Ukrainian is the official language of Ukraine, although Russian was also widely spoken in the eastern and southern regions. <emphasis role="bold">Language choice can be a sensitive issue, so it’s important to use the language preferred by your communication partner</emphasis>. Many Ukrainians do not understand medical language and have difficulty communicating abstract concepts or understanding American dialects. <emphasis role="bold">It is recommended to use a professional interpreter, speak slowly and clearly with a medium tone of voice. Refrain from a loud conversation when communicating with Ukrainian immigrants.</emphasis>
                        </para>
                     </listitem>
                     <listitem>
                        <para role="Para">Ukrainians appreciate active listening. <emphasis role="bold">Provide full attention when someone is talking with you. Nodding and making affirmative sounds may show that you are engaged in the conversation and appreciate the speaker</emphasis>.</para>
                     </listitem>
                     <listitem>
                        <para role="Para">Ukrainians may prefer to avoid confrontational or aggressive communication styles. <emphasis role="bold">It’s essential to be aware of regional and individual differences when interacting with Ukrainians</emphasis> in any setting to ensure effective communication.</para>
                     </listitem>
                     <listitem>
                        <para role="Para">Punctuality is a cultural standard. Many Ukrainians arrive early for their scheduled appointments.</para>
                     </listitem>
                     <listitem>
                        <para role="Para">Ukrainians accept touch in the healthcare settings but prefer not to be hugged or kissed by strangers. A handshake is acceptable. They do not appreciate nonverbal gestures such as standing with hands inserted into pockets or arms crossed over the chest. Neither do they appreciate slouching postures when being interviewed. Ukrainians are likely to seek and follow the healthcare recommendation which may appear paternalistic in the Western healthcare system.</para>
                     </listitem>
                     <listitem>
                        <para role="Para ParaOneEmphasisChild">
                           <emphasis role="bold">Address Ukrainians by their last name and title such as Mr., Mrs., Miss, and Ms. You can greet patients with a handshake.</emphasis>
                        </para>
                     </listitem>
                  </itemizedlist>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0034s0001s0002" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">34.1.2 </emphasis> Family Roles and Organization</title>
            <para role="Para">Ukrainian family roles are influenced by traditional and cultural norms, but there can be variation in family structures and roles depending on factors such as urban or rural living, generational differences, and individual preferences, there are some common characteristics of Ukrainian family life.</para>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Extended families with multiple generations living together were common in Ukraine. Extended family arrangement may be less common in urban areas. Extended families provide emotional and financial support and play a role in child-rearing. <emphasis role="bold">Ask patients who they want to be a healthcare surrogate and to include in the medical decisions making process. Do not disclose sexual same-sex orientation to family members.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Traditional gender roles</emphasis> are still prevalent in Ukraine. Men may be seen as the primary breadwinners, while women are expected to take care of the household and children. However, women have equal decision-making power and some families may be described as maternalistic. In urban areas among younger generations, gender roles are more equitable with women pursuing careers and men taking more domestic responsibilities.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Child-rearing</emphasis>: Children’s education is highly valued in the Ukrainian culture. Parents, grandparents, and all members of the extended family may play roles in the care and education of children. There is a strong emphasis on education. Parents invest in children’s academic success. <emphasis role="bold">Include grandparents and older family members in health education for their grandchildren.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Respect for elders</emphasis> is a fundamental aspect of Ukrainian family life. Grandparents are highly respected and are often involved in the lives of their grandchildren. Elders are often consulted for advice and play a significant role in decision-making within the family. <emphasis role="bold">Help families prevent caregiver burden. Provide resources about long-term care facilities if needed and encourage family to visit the facility before a decision is made to place a family member there.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Marriage and family values are highly valued. Many Ukrainians place a strong emphasis on the importance of a stable and loving family unit. Divorce rates, while rising, are generally lower compared to some Western countries. Families often provide financial support to their members including assistance with education, housing, or other major life events. Family dynamics are evolving in Ukraine among younger generations. There is a growing emphasis on individualism, career aspirations, and personal choices. Ongoing political and war crisis led to changes in family roles and organization as well as family structures and gender roles.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Religious institutions</emphasis> have a meaningful influence on family life. Religious ceremonies and traditions are often integrated into family events such as weddings and baptisms.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Hospitality</emphasis>: Ukrainians are known for their cheerful family gatherings with extended family members coming together for celebrations and holidays. Food plays a significant role in these gatherings with elaborate traditional meals shared with loved ones.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Emigration</emphasis>: During the last 30 years, economic and political instability have led to a significant emigration of Ukrainians in search of better opportunities abroad. This has sometimes resulted in family members being separated across borders adding emotional challenges to families.</para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0034s0001s0003" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">34.1.3 </emphasis> Workforce Issues</title>
            <para role="Para">Before emigration to the United States, about 70% of the Ukrainians were living in big cities residing in apartments. About 30% of Ukrainians live in rural areas and work on farms. Western Ukraine is more rural, while Eastern Ukraine is heavily industrialized. Nevertheless, many young people leave the countryside to live and work in the cities.</para>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Ukrainians have a strong <emphasis role="bold">work ethic</emphasis> and dedication to their jobs. Ukrainians value professionalism in the workplace. This includes dressing appropriately and being respectful to colleagues. Ukrainians communicate directly with colleagues and friends, and this is considered a sign of respect and sincerity. Not showing up for work without prior notification is considered disrespectful. Ukrainians practice politeness, respect, and accountability in the workplace. They value time and support the rule of work and society.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Punctuality</emphasis> is generally expected in the workplace. Being late for meetings or appointments is considered disrespectful so it’s important to arrive on time.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Ukrainians may practice non-direct eye contact when speaking with government officials, a practice common in Ukraine where making eye contact with government officials could lead to questioning or even invasion of personal space or disrespect. <emphasis role="bold">Do not assume that the lack of eye contact means the person is not paying attention, does not care, or not providing correct information.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">The tone of voice may be loud as Ukrainians prefer to prove their point of view by articulating loudly. <emphasis role="bold">Do not interpret a loud voice volume as a sign of anger.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0034s0001s0004" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">34.1.4 </emphasis> Biocultural Ecology</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Ukrainians who have immigrated to the United States are predominately white Caucasians and have a physical structure like other white Americans, making them prone to skin cancer.</para>
                  <para role="Para ParaOneEmphasisChild">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Encourage the use of sunblock and instruct all family members about the dangers of skin cancer.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Ukrainian immigrant may have prior exposure to tuberculosis. The burden of tuberculosis (TB) remains significant according to WHO estimates. Ukraine has the fourth highest TB incidence (new cases and relapses) among the 53 countries of the WHO European Region. Other chronic infectious diseases are hepatitis and HIV.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Ukraine’s population faces health risks from a poor diet, smoking, alcohol consumption, and lack of regular physical activity.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Men are more likely to be exposed to these behavioral risk factors than women.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Mental health remains a significant challenge. The adult male suicide rate in Ukraine is the highest in the WHO European Region (WHO <emphasis role="CitationRef">
                        <link linkend="ch0034s0003bib13">2021</link>
                     </emphasis>).</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Physical, psychiatric trauma, and post-traumatic stress disorder can be prevalent conditions in new Ukrainian immigrants due to war exposure and economic and healthcare destruction of the country. Fewer than 2% of Ukrainians seek specialized psychological or psychiatric help and may have impaired social functioning. <emphasis role="bold">Evaluate patients’ risk factors for depression, suicide, and post-traumatic stress disorder. Younger age, lack of social support, psychiatric co-morbidities, and substance use disorder are significant.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">The government spending on health in Ukraine is the lowest compared to the European countries, leaving vulnerable groups at risk of impoverishing payments and undermining access to health services. Over half (51%) of all health spending in Ukraine in 2018 was private almost entirely consisting of out-of-pocket payments. <emphasis role="bold">Explain patient governmental resources and structure of healthcare to facilitate obtaining insurance and using healthcare services.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
            <para role="Para">Table <emphasis role="InternalRef">
                  <link linkend="ch0034s0001ta01">34.1</link>
               </emphasis> lists commonly occurring health conditions for Ukrainians in three categories: lifestyle, environment, and genetics.</para>
            <table id="ch0034s0001ta01">
               <title>
                  <emphasis role="CaptionNumber">Table 34.1</emphasis> Top 10 health risk factors common to Ukrainians</title>
               <tgroup cols="2">
                  <colspec colname="c1" colnum="1"/>
                  <colspec colname="c2" colnum="2"/>
                  <tbody>
                     <row>
                        <entry>
                           <para role="SimplePara">Health condition</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                           <para role="SimplePara">Cause</para>
                        </entry>
                     </row>
