         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0034s0001s0005" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">34.1.5 </emphasis> High-Risk Health Behaviors</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Smoking is a prevalent health risk behavior in Ukraine with a high rate among men. Smoking is a major contributor to respiratory diseases, cardiovascular diseases, and cancer. <emphasis role="bold">Encourage smoking cessation and assist with finding smoking cessation programs.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Ukraine has one of the highest alcohol consumption rates in the world. High levels of alcohol consumption contribute to a range of health problems, including liver disease, alcohol poisoning, accidents, and violence.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Ukrainian diets are high in salt, saturated fats, and sugar, which can lead to obesity, hypertension, and other diet-related diseases. Insufficient consumption of fruits and vegetables is also a concern.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">A sedentary lifestyle, particularly in urban areas, can contribute to obesity and high levels of diabetes and cardiovascular diseases.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Unprotected sex and a lack of access to oral contraception as well as awareness about sexually transmitted infections (STIs) lead to the spread of STIs, including HIV/AIDS. <emphasis role="bold">Explain support services in the United States for intimate partner violence. Help patients gain an access to the services.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Injection drug use</emphasis> is a significant risk factor for the spread of HIV/AIDS and hepatitis C in Ukraine.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Ukrainians may have <emphasis role="bold">low vaccination rates</emphasis> for preventable diseases. Inquire about prior vaccinations, and advise about possible health risks, especially among children.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Some Ukrainian cities, particularly Kyiv and industrial areas, have <emphasis role="bold">high level of air pollution</emphasis> which contribute to respiratory problems and cardiovascular diseases in Ukrainians.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Lack of awareness about mental health issues can deter individuals from seeking help and leading to potentially risky behaviors. <emphasis role="bold">Screen all newer immigrants for conditions common in their home country. Provide scientific information and assist in finding appropriate services and resources.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0034s0001s0006" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">34.1.6 </emphasis> Nutrition</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">The Ukrainian diet includes pork, beef, goat, lamb, rabbits, chicken, duck, fish, and various cold-cut products made from pork such as ham, sausage, and bacon. Ukrainians eat large amounts of vegetables such as potatoes, cabbage, tomatoes, cucumbers, and eggplants, cooked and pickled. Breads are among staple foods: white, sour dough, dark rye, and numerous sweetened choices. Grains are popular as a side dish. A prevalent grain is buckwheat, called <emphasis>kasha.</emphasis> Popular drinks include tea, coffee, kvas, cocoa, kefir (special soured milk drink), honey and cherry liquor, and vodka with pepper (horilka).</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Traditional Ukrainian dishes include <emphasis>varenyky, borsch,</emphasis> holubtsi, and <emphasis>holushki.</emphasis> Varenyky consists of boiled dumplings filled with potatoes, sauerkraut, cheese, or cherries. Ukrainians eat dumplings with sour cream-fried onions or bacon bits. Borsch is a soup of meat, beets, carrots, tomatoes, and cabbage served with bread and sour cream. Holubtsi are stuffed cabbage rolls filled with rice, buckwheat, and meat.</para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0034s0001s0007" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">34.1.7 </emphasis> Pregnancy and Childbearing Practices</title>
            <para role="Para">Pregnancy and childbearing practices are similar to the Russian culture.</para>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Contraception for Ukrainian women is allowed without sanctions or taboos. Condoms, followed by intrauterine devices and birth control pills are available. Ukrainian males do not consider vasectomies as a method of contraception. Many new immigrants may not be aware of different methods of fertility control.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para ParaOneEmphasisChild">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Inform patients of the variety of birth control methods common in the United States.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Pregnant women have regular prenatal checkups, which are mandatory in Ukraine. During pregnancy, women are encouraged to rest. They do not perform heavy lifting, hard work, and strenuous physical activities; they are also protected from bad news or unpleasant information that can be harmful to the fetus. Pregnant women are encouraged to eat foods that are high in iron, calcium, and vitamins. Strawberries, citrus fruits, peanuts, and chocolate are avoided to prevent allergies in the newborn.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">As labor approaches, women take laxatives and enemas to facilitate delivery. Recently husbands in Ukraine are allowed to participate in the delivery or visit the hospital postpartum. There are no cultural restrictions for fathers or female relatives not to participate in delivery in United States. <emphasis role="bold">Ask patients who they wish to be involved in the delivery.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Breastfeeding is encouraged as Ukrainians believe that breast milk will increase immune system of the newborn. Some women breast-feed until the infant reaches the toddler stage.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Peri-care with warm water is important, and a binder is worn to help the mother’s figure return to normal.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">In Ukraine, women receive maternity leave before delivery and after newborn delivery up to the 3 years. <emphasis role="bold">Explain family medical leave practices for expectant parents in the United States.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0034s0001s0008" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">34.1.8 </emphasis> Death Rituals</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Ukrainian’ families protect the terminally ill family member. They want to be notified about imminent death first before the patient is told.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Most families prefer to care for the dying family member at home.</para>
                  <para role="Para ParaOneEmphasisChild">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Facilitate transferring the dying person to the home if the family wishes and has the means to provide terminal care. Assist with obtaining hospice home care.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Ukrainian families believe that everything should be done to save a loved one and often will not agree to disconnect the life support. They will not discuss advance directive, a living will, durable power of attorney, do not resuscitate procedures, and might not sign these documents. Ukrainian Orthodox pastor may perform and institute a special prayer, hymn, and vigil over the deceased.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para ParaOneEmphasisChild">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Ask permission from the family before contacting clergy for their preferences.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Ukrainian rural families may not accept cremation; most prefer interment. Ukrainians living in the major cities may consider cremation.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Both men and women may wear black as a sign of mourning and mirrors are covered of the deceased’s home. Expression of grief varies greatly. Ukrainian Orthodox family mourns the death of a family member for at least 40 days. <emphasis role="bold">Recognize a wide variety of grieving and bereavement practices in Ukrainian culture.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0034s0001s0009" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">34.1.9 </emphasis> Spirituality</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Ukrainians are closely associated with the Ukrainian Orthodox Church and Catholic Church. Faith plays a role in internal spirituality. The Ukrainian government recognizes Orthodox Christianity, Buddhism, Islam, and Judaism as established religions.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Ukrainian Americans often practice religion and attend services in Ukrainian Churches. <emphasis role="bold">Discuss individual religious practices and spirituality with patients and family during the interview.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0034s0001s0010" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">34.1.10 </emphasis> Healthcare Practices</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Most Ukrainians define <emphasis>health</emphasis> as the absence of disease.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Ukrainian immigrants will need to become more familiar with the healthcare insurance system in the United States as Ukraine has a public healthcare system. Some clinics and hospitals in Ukraine are private, and patients pay out of pocket for their treatment. <emphasis role="bold">Explain health reimbursement procedures in the United States and elicit assistance from case managers to obtain health insurance coverage as needed.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Hospitalization in Ukraine lasts between 3 and 4 weeks. Some patients may expect the same in the United States. Explain the hospitalization stays in the United States. <emphasis role="bold">Refer patient to the home health care agencies if needed upon discharge and teach family how to care for recuperating family member at home.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Single females do not do Pap tests in Ukraine; only, married women perform them in women center clinics. Explain the significance of Pap tests and mammography, regardless of the woman’s marital status.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Many individuals prefer staying warm to prevent colds and other illnesses. Most like to keep the temperature warm in their rooms. They may also be unwilling to add ice or drink cold drinks with ice. Explain the application of ice compress in exact terms. <emphasis role="bold">Ask if a patient wants ice in their drinks.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Most Ukrainians consider pain a sign of weakness or fear of side effects of opioid medications and may not ask for pain medicine. <emphasis role="bold">Offer and encourage pain medicine and explain that it will help with the healing process.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Patients are not comfortable to being told about terminal diagnoses or cancer because it is believed to make the condition worse. <emphasis role="bold">Inform patients about poor prognosis gradually on their terms and preferably in several meetings. Consult with family members first and pay attention on their verbal and nonverbal cues for readiness to hear news about a terminal illness.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Cupping is a common procedure in Ukraine for treatment of a respiratory infection in healthcare settings and at home. Do not mistake circular ecchymotic areas on children or adults back as abuse. <emphasis role="bold">Ask if they have been practicing cupping.</emphasis> Alcohol-saturated cotton or other materials is introduced to a cup. The cotton or material is lighted inside the cup and removed; then, the hot cup is turned upside down on the patient’s back. The skin is drawn into the cup by vacuum. The cup is pulled off the skin within 10–15 min leaving round ecchymotic areas 1–1½ in. in diameter.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Common cultural practices include using herbal remedies and tinctures available from pharmacies, soaking one’s feet in warm water for a cold, gargling with salty water for sore throat, aromatherapy for a variety of respiratory illnesses, mud and mineral baths to promote healing, and herbs and teas for fever and colds. <emphasis role="bold">Incorporate nonharmful folk practices into allopathic prescriptions.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Ukrainians are accustomed to seeing multiple healthcare providers. Each provider may give prescriptions. <emphasis role="bold">Specifically ask patients if they are seeing other healthcare providers and taking any prescription medications, over-the-counter medications, or traditional herbal remedies and teas.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Ukrainians may not disclose any mental health issues unless they are experiencing crisis. They might present with vague somatic complaints because mental illness carries a significant stigma and is considered as a weakness. <emphasis role="bold">Screen for anxiety, depression, and post-traumatic stress disorder in immigrants.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Ukrainians may have a great fear of contracting HIV from blood transfusions. <emphasis role="bold">Explain US safety procedures with blood transfusions and organ donation.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
         <sect2 id="ch0034s0001s0011" role="Heading">
            <title>
               <emphasis role="HeadingNumber">34.1.11 </emphasis> Healthcare Providers</title>
            <itemizedlist role="UnorderedListMarkBullet">
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Healthcare providers are very well respected by Ukrainian immigrants. Because nurses’ function in higher roles in the United States, Ukrainian immigrants may not understand their independent roles. <emphasis role="bold">Explain the roles and education of nurses in the United States.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para">Men and women are accustomed to living together in very small apartments or in communal living; thus, most do not have a problem with privacy. Healthcare professionals’ gender is not generally a concern in providing care.</para>
               </listitem>
               <listitem>
                  <para role="Para ParaOneEmphasisChild">
                     <emphasis role="bold">Always ask about gender concerns before performing breast pelvic or rectal exams on patients.</emphasis>
                  </para>
               </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
         </sect2>
      </sect1>
      <sect1 id="ch0034s0002" role="Heading">
         <sect1info>
            <risinfo>
               <booktitle>Handbook for Culturally Competent Care</booktitle>
               <isbn>1316139783031</isbn>
               <chapternumber>34</chapternumber>
               <chapterid>ch0034</chapterid>
               <chaptertitle>34. People of Ukrainian Heritage</chaptertitle>
               <authorgroup>
                  <author>
                     <personname>
                        <firstname>Eric A.</firstname>
                        <surname>Fenkl</surname>
                     </personname>
                  </author>
                  <author>
                     <personname>
                        <firstname>Larry D.</firstname>
                        <surname>Purnell</surname>
                     </personname>
                  </author>
               </authorgroup>
               <publisher>
                  <publishername>Springer International Publishing</publishername>
               </publisher>
               <pubdate>2024</pubdate>
            </risinfo>
